text: full toss from round the wicket, 96kph and clubbed to the deep midwicket sweeper for one
preText:
Phil Salt is scratching out his guard, and it looks like spin to open for Royals: Bjorn Fortuin limbering up

5.28pm: Right then, here come the players. Royals, by chasing, will have the slight advantage in knowing exactly what score they will need in order to keep their NRR above DSG. Shall we do this?

Noor: "@Afeef, Parnell, their regular captain and an important bowler for the side wasn't available too. That's an important factor."

5.20pm: So there are various permutations for tonight, with the only thing certain that Capitals will top the table. Should they win, but Royals confirm their passage in fourth spot, then these two teams will (I think) face off again tomorrow in Joburg. Wayne Parnell has now missed two matches with the niggle he picked up during Capitals win over MICT at the weekend, but de Bruyn said they were still hopeful he might be able to return for the semi

Here's friend of the SA20 and feedback regular, Afeef: "Despite being the best team of the tournament, Pretoria's defeat in the last match was mind-boggling. Conceded a huge total and absolutely folded in response."

5pm: Royals won the toss and will bowl. "We like to chase and it's normally a chasing ground," says David Miller. "Firstly we want to win, so that's our priority. Nothing changes for us." Three changes for Royals, Paul Stirling, Eoin Morgan and Codi Yusuf coming in. Theunis de Bruyn, Capitals' stand-in captain, is happy enough batting first. "We know that we're going to be playing at the Wanderers tomorrow [in the first semi-final], so chance to put a big score on the board and try to defend it. Now's the business part of the competition, we've played good cricket and excited for the next few days." Adil Rashid and Anrich Nortje return for Capitals, after their thrashing at the hands of DSG two nights ago

Pretoria Capitals: 1 Phil Salt, 2 Kusal Mendis, 3 Theunis de Bruyn, 4 Rilee Rossouw, 5 Colin Ingram, 6 James Neesham, 7 Senuran Muthusamy, 8 Migael Pretorius, 9 Eathan Bosch, 10 Adil Rashid, 11 Anrich Nortje

Paarl Rocks: 1 Paul Stirling, 2 Jason Roy, 3 Jos Buttler, 4 Mitchell van Buuren, 5 David Miller, 6 Eoin Morgan, 7 Evan Jones, 8 Andile Phelukwayo 9 Bjorn Fortuin, 10 Codi Yusuf, 11 Lungi Ngidi

4.45pm: Hello and welcome. It's crunch time in the SA20 group stage, with Pretoria Capitals hosting Paarl Rocks Royals for a do-or-die final contest. Well, sort of. Perhaps do-or-not-die-too-badly would be more accurate... Royals are currently sitting fourth on the table, in the final semi-final spot, and will stay there unless they lose too heavily to leaders Capitals - by 62 runs or with eight overs to spare, to be precise. A defeat of that magnitude would allow Durban's Super Giants, also currently on 19 points, to sneak ahead. And just in case you're thinking that's pretty unlikely, the last two results in the comp have been victories by 76 runs and a whopping 151 runs (DSG keeping their hopes alive by hammering Capitals). So there's no complacency here, thankyouverymuch. Toss and teams coming up shortly

preText: Ten to qualify from eight balls... It's looking healthier now...

text: a big wipe at the legbreak, misses out... and that's the end of that
postText:
Time for the presentations.

David Miller: "We wanted to go out and win the game but got into a sticky situation so reassessed. They batted really well but there are areas we have to chat about... not a great game for us in all departments but we're in the semi-finals. We've got matchwinners all the way through, Jos showed class and maturity, but we have to come together and put a big performance in tomorrow. It'll be different conditions, a new game, we'll be up for it."

Kusal Mendis is Player of the Match. "Good start in the first six overs... I was happy with my innings, everyone looked to make runs, chasing 200 easily... the team is very together, we know how to play, got on really well in the last two games.

Theunis de Bruyn "Nice to win, to be honest we would have liked to keep them out and face the team that gave us a hiding the other day... but we play to win, and same opposition in different conditions. Will assess tomorrow. We've played as a unit throughout the competition and we play to win."

So on that, it's a wrap. We're into the final four. Capitals vs Royals, and JSK versus Sunrisers, for a place in the inaugural SA20 final. See you tomorrow, same time, different place!

9.07pm So... that was a bit tense! As 59-run wins go, that was a cliffhanger... and the upshot is that these two go again in the first semi-final tomorrow night, as Durban's faint hopes were raised from the dead only to be dashed again.

A thumping display from Pretoria, powered by some stunning hitting from Mendis, Salt, Neesham and Ingram, who seemed to be playing on a different surface. In reply, Jos Buttler's innings looked imposing in the final analysis, but his 70 from 45 was an unusually sketchy affair by his standards, and he lacked any meaningful support in the tense latter stages of the chase.

Sumer mehta: "The most victorious hammering I've ever seen"

Bhargav : "Based on the capitals mindset. I think Paarl Royals are going to make the final tomorrow. Capitals will regret this stupidity "

wkt_text: F du Plessis c Rashid Khan b Linde 0 (3m 1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: Round the wicket, action straightaway as Linde lands it on a length and gets it to turn viciously outside off, he had to reach for it and spoons it straight to Rashid Khan at short cover, the third umpire is taking a look at it, he dived full-length to take a screamer and the big fish du Plessis goes without scoring! What a start for MICT
preText:
The players are out in the middle

MI Cape Town have won the toss and decided to field first

Hello everyone. Welcome to ESPNCricinfo's coverage of SA20 where Joburg Super Kings and MI Cape Town will square off this evening in Johannesburg. Super Kings are through to the semi-final while MI Cape Town are coming off a nerve-jangling affair that they lost by the barest of margins against Pretoria Capitals. MI Cape Town will be looking to sign off from the tournament on a high and take away some positives from this season. The air is buzzing in Johannesburg and the Wanderers Stadium is buzzing. Flags waving and the atmosphere is electric! It's sunny, gorgeous and there is no chance of rain

Faf du Plessis, who is ageing like fine wine, hogged the limelight once again at the Wanderers to guide Super Kings into the SA20 semi-finals. The former South Africa captain rollicked to 92 off 61 deliveries that got his side to 160/6 in the last match. Reeza Hendricks looks in fine touch as well; he played the supporting role by scoring 40 runs. Kings' bowling unit is a well-oiled machine with Maheesh Theekshana and Gerald Coetzee conjuring up wickets at crucial junctures of the game. Also, the new kid on the block, Kyle Simmons wreaked havoc on Sunriser's middle order, returning brilliant figures of 3/23 in the last game.

On the other hand, Rashid Khan bowled his heart out and only conceded 17 runs in his spell to keep his team in the hunt but Pretoria Capitals prevailed in the thriller on Saturday evening. The veteran Rassie van der Dussen had earlier set the platform with his brisk 51 but he didn't get much help from his teammates which hurt their cause. One of the bright spots for Cape Town has been the teenage sensation Dewald Brevis who plays with an uninhibited approach and it will be exciting to see how he fares in this game.

wkt_text: D Brevis  b Coetzee 27 (53m 26b 0x4 2x6) SR: 103.84
text: Sounds the death rattle! Slower one on a hard length, jags back and pings the leg stump as he plays all over it. Joburg Super Kings register an emphatic win over MI Cape Town, winning by 76 runs!
postText:
Faf du Plessis: I was thinking how do you play that ball, the arm-ball and half-tracker that should have been dispatched for four. Probably hit a patch and spun, the only ball that did that in the whole game. The powerplay is important, you could see the way that Wade played, the intensity, the way he played those laps, good options for him. du Plooy is having a great time, such maturity for such a young guy. It is not an old-school Jo'Burg wicket. It would have been great to have had a home semifinal but we are switching venues. A bowler's graveyard there so we have to change our plans and come back.

Leus du Plooy, Player of the Match: It was tough to time it the whole innings. Luckily we had a chance to play on it yesterday and we got to a good total. I asked him if it was outside off and I'm sure he (Wade) will get me a beer later. It is a fantastic tournament to be a part of, a fantastic environment to be a part of with a captain like Faf and a coach like Fleming who has won so many IPL titles. I'm gonna keep improving and learning.

Rashid Khan: The way we started with the ball we were under control but in the middle, we did not execute our plans. We gave runs and those runs cost us. It was not a wicket of 190. Something to learn and next time is going to be much better. Overall if you look into this competition, we did not take the game deep and with the batting we haven't scored enough. In the last 10 games, we have scored just two-three fifties. 120 is a lot of balls to play and that's something to look into. When it was time for us to score runs, we lost wickets. I absolutely loved it, every stadium is packed and how successful this competition is. I feel after IPL this is gonna be a massive competition and the second-best league.

Joburg Super Kings register a clinical win over MI Cape Town and they barely put a foot wrong tonight putting up an above-par 189 on the board thanks to Leus du Plooy's onslaught - which was one for the memory vault - as he hit 11 fours and one maximum, striking at 168.75 for his blistering 81-run-knock. Thereon, Matthew Wade's counter-attacking, brave, nimble-footed 40 off 18 balls coupled with handy contributions from the lower order got them to a competitive total.

Even though George Linde got Faf du Plessis out on the very first delivery, JSK didn't stray from their plans and kept going hard at MICT bowlers. Reeza Hendricks departed early in the piece as well but the run-rate didn't drop. In reply, MI Cape Town batters got starts but couldn't convert them into substantial scores as the bowling from JSK remained spot on with rare looseners. The spinners - Maheesh Theekshana and Kyle Simmons - spun a web around the batters, not allowing them to tee off and picked up wickets whenever batters were getting some semblance of control. As a result of well-knit bowling performance, JSK were always in the driver's seat and the game never seemed slipping away from them.

And that conludes live coverage of this game. Until next time, it's goodbye from me (Rvel Zahid) and Ranjith.

preText:
Players and umpires are out in the middle and play is about to start.

Pretoria Capitals: +Philip Salt, Kusal Mendis, *Theunis de Bruyn, Rilee Rossouw, Colin Ingram, James Neesham, Senuran Muthusamy, Migael Pretorius, Eathan Bosch, Daryn Dupavillon, Joshua Little.

Durban Super Giants: Ben McDermott, *Quinton de Kock, Matthew Breetzke, Keemo Paul, +Heinrich Klaasen, Wiaan Mulder, Dwaine Pretorius, David Willey, Keshav Maharaj, Junior Dala, Reece Topley.

Toss: Pretoria Capitals win the toss and opt to bowl.

Capitals are leading the points table with 27 and they still play two more games including this. Super Giants are at number 5 with 14 points and it is their last league game.

In their last encounter between these two, Super Giants were fold for just 80 and Capitals won convincingly by 8 wickets.

Hello and welcome for the 28th match of the tournament. It is between Pretoria Capitals and Durban's Super Giants at Centurion.

preText:
1:31pm: Smuts will bowl the first over. Du Plessia and Hendricks will open, the former will take strike

1:28pm: It's a sunny afternoon. Sold out says, Mike Haysman on air. Remember, the winning team of the game confirms qualification. Umpires walk out. Fielders get into a huddle. The batters come out as the pep talk finishes. Pictures look lovely, lots of yellow in the crowd.

Doctor V: "Playing xi?" Here it is. Literally what the doctor ordered. Teams wise, Super Kings' batting has been bolstered by Matthew Wade. Shepherd can hit big but he is a bowling allrounder at No. 7. Sunrisers on paper, have seven bowling bowling options with Smuts and Markram. Adam Rossington is in form which is a positive for them with the bat.

Aiden Markram, Sunrisers captain were going to bowl, so they're happy with it. Doesn't think it'll change too much, and hopes to restrict Super Kings and chase it down later. He says the ground is unique, most grounds in South Africa are different. Says Wanderers generally offers pace and bounce but has taken spin in the last two years, so they've done homework on the conditions and ultimately play the game out in the middle. Says they want to play a great game and gain confidence and momentum. One change: Fuller is back for Ottneil Baartman.

Faf du Plessis, Super Kings captain says the track is a bit dry, hopes it'll slow down as the cracks open up. Says the weather looks alright. The team is in a good position but they don't want to be complacent having played played two good games. Same team as the last game.

1:02pm: Super Kings win the toss and bat

Both teams had washouts in different cities a couple of days ago but it's a balmy day in Joburg.

12:45pm: It's Sunrisers Eastern Cape's final game in the group stage of the season. They sit comfortably at No. 2 on the Points Table and will look to head into the semis on a positive note. For Joburg Super Giants, there's a game today and tomorrow and they are likely to reach the semis thanks to Durban Super Giants' poor net run rate and four fewer points having played one extra game. But Super Kings wouldn't like to allow Super Giants an outside chance to qualify. Given that context, let's find out how these two teams go against each other. Toss coming soon. Stay tuned.

postText:
Hendricks chats after the innings: "Another great knock from Faf... It is two-paced, and slightly slow. It assisted the spinners as well."

3.08pm From 119 for 0 to 152 for 6 at one stage, Super Kings lose steam, as their batting lost way around du Plessis' 92. His opening partner Hendricks made 40 while playing anchor, but no one else got into double figures. It looked like the pitch slowed down with time - no doubt Super Kings were headed for around 170-180 in the 15th over - as the cutters and change of pace came into play. Join Ekanth for the chase, as Eastern Cape look to finish the season with a win.

postText:
That's it from us today, with Super Kings making it to the semi-final, alongside Pretoria Capitals. But you can hop over to the action between Durban's Super Giants and Capitals, as we bid you goodbye from this game. Thanks for your company!

Faf du Plessis is the Player of the Match

5.07pm Only two batters from both teams' top eight entered double figures - which summed their batting as much as the challenge that this slowish pitch presented - as du Plessis' 92 overshadowed them all. Bavuma got 50 for Eastern Cape in return, but for nothing. Super Kings lost 6 for 33 after a dominating opening stand; Eastern Cape collapsed with 6 for 51 when things seemed in control.

shortText: Parnell to van der Dussen, no run
text: it's back of a length, punched into the offside. Clear cries of "No, no, no!"
preText:
Wesley Marshall, playing his first game this tournament, will open the batting alongside good old Rassie van der Dussen. Parnell to bowl the first ball

While we wait, here are the the Playing XIs

J Pearce: "One of the changes will be no Will Jacks!! He's in New Zealand." Either that or he's got one hell of a commute.

Pretoria Capitals have won the toss and will bowl first. "In terms of being match ready, MICT are probably more match-ready," says Wayne Parnell, whose side hasn't played in 12 days. There's a few changes, which we should have for you shortly.

Rashid also says he would have "obviously" bowled first. The usual stuff about the toss not being in their hands etc etc. "We need to do the basics right," says Rashid, reaching into that bag of cliches and picking out another classic. More pertinently, Sam Curran is back and Beuran Hendricks is out. There's another change, too, mind.

Hello and welcome, folks! After a bit of a damp squib yesterday, hopefully we have clearer skies and fuller games to satiate your appetite today. Pretoria Capitals take on the beleagured MI Cape Town, with the toss minutes away

postText: And Wayne Parnell does walk in now, ahead of Josh Little. Just a run a ball needed, with two wickets standing

preText: Is that the game? Defeat for MI will all but end their hopes of progressing, remember

preText: Sam Curran to bowl, Capitals' limping captain, Wayne Parnell, on strike

text: back of a length, swiped into the covers and Parnell is struggling... but the throw to Curran is poor, he can't gather and Parnell hops grimacing over the line!
preText: Here's Vinod Rajpal with a crunch prediction: "Gut feeling, MI will come back in last over and keep their hopes alive in this league, experience from IPL. Mark my words Alan!"

wkt_text: S Muthusamy c Brevis b Curran 25 (40m 23b 2x4 2x6) SR: 108.69
text: full, sliced to backward point... Curran celebrates, and Capitals are nine down! Unless it was a bump ball? No, it's definitely gone up off the outside edge as Muthusamy chops his bat down into the turf. Snapped up by Brevis, and MI are alive! Sam Curran doing the business with his third of the night
postText: Josh Little is going to have to come out and try to win this on SA20 debut! Two to win off three

text: on the pads, through to Roelofson... given as wide! Rashid is saying it flicked Little's pads, though. He wants to review, in order to get that extra scratched off... and Allahudien Paleker does send it upstairs. Definitely brushed the pad, according to UltraEdge, so the wide is rescinded!
postText: Two off two

text: full in the channel, Little swings and misses! Dot ball and this chase is going right to the wire!
postText: MI need to win this. Parnell at the other end can't run. Two needed, all eyes on Curran vs Little. Slip in in place, everyone in tight on the one

text: full toss, slapped over cover! Curran blinks at the last moment, as Capitals scramble through for two to win by one wicket! Little and Parnell exchange a grin, not the best connection but it had enough to clear the infield. A thrilling game ends with victory for the home side, and MICT's hopes of reaching the top four are effectively over
postText: 9.35pm: What a finish we've seen in Centurion. Nineteen wickets, several impressive performances, and the result going down to the final delivery. MI will rue their collapse with the bat, which included being bowled out with two deliveries to spare - how important could a couple more runs have been? Capitals are secure at the top of the table, they are definitely going through to the knockouts; but for highly fancied MICT it's back to the drawing board until next year, barring a miraculous set of results. Anyway, that concludes our coverage for tonight, join us for more SA20 frolics tomorrow. Thanks for your comments, from myself, Danyal and Ranjith, it's goodnight. Bye!

text: magnificent timing from the teenager. Times it back down the ground, and the new ball speeds away for a boundary
preText:
David Willey to open the bowling.

The players have strolled out, as have the officials. We're moments away. Roelofsen, the chap who keeps my O's and E's honest, will open alongside Dewald Brevis. It's quite overcast, mind you.

With the game a few minutes away, here are the two XIs

Imraan: "This tournament has been very successful because the main reason if it's success is the best time of the year in South Africa."

DSG have won the toss and they will field first. Quinny confirms he won't be keeping because his fingers still a bit sore, but he'll be batting in the same position.

"We would have liked to bowl first, too" Says the usual things about how they'll need to bat well, that DSG are a very good side, etc etc. "Pretty hard on the guys who also played the England ODIs," he points out. Tim David is back, mind you. We'll have the XIs for you shortly becuase there's no way I remembered every name Rashid just threw out at Polly.

Hello! We're about to kick things off here in Durban. The busines of the 3-match ODI series is done, and we're back to hedonistic T20 fun. The Durban Super Giants against MICT - bring it on.

shortText: Rashid Khan to Breetzke, no run
text: given leg before after a confident appeal! But hang on, Breetzke has reviewed. It's not a no-ball first up. Breetzke skipped down the pitch, as Rashid bowled on the fuller side of a length, getting the ball to turn away and end on what looked like middle stump. Breetzke was trying to clip from off stump, and replays indicate a faint - and a near invisible - inside edge when ball is close to the bat. So the decision is overturned

They tried to sneak a leg bye, even as Rashid's direct hit at the non-striker's end - after he nearly ended near the keeper - means Breetzke is safely home. preText: 4 from 3

text: flung away over fine leg! Victory for Super Giants in style. Breetzke breezes that away over fine leg for six. Jansen bowled short and just outside leg, as Breetzke was standing with a touch of room. The length and line ended up being just perfect, as he swung that to seal the win
postText:
That's it from us today, as Super Giants gain four points to keep the SA20 interesting in its latter parts. But they need more of it from the two remaining games. Anyway, I direct you to our SA20 wrap for all updates and news from the tournament so far. And until tomorrow, it is goodnight and goodbye from Ranjith, Danyal and me, Himanshu!

Quinton de Kock, Super Giants' captain, is the Player of the Match: "It was important to score runs... They put a lot of pressure up front. I feel like I'm best suited at No. 5 as a finisher! Myself and KG have always had battles... It's still a matter of trying to win the game. We still need to two more."

Rashid Khan speaks first: "It was a competitive total, but we were 15-20 short. But the way we bowled in the last 10 overs was good to see... We just have to win the last two games. Every game is like a knockout for us. It was a kind of wicket where we could score 190, but it got harder to bat on with the extra bounce."

Time for the presentations

9.18pm Four points for Super Giants, although they remain at the bottom of the table. They will need a few bonus points to make those immediately above them nervous yet, as they are still one behind the fifth-placed team. The chase was set up by de Kock's 63 and Paul's whirlwind 31, as Breetzke ensured his side went home with a win with a 48* of his own. Hang around for the presentations.

text: carved over backward point first ball for four. It's a fast outfield and looks like a short boundary, which means third man has no chance of getting there
preText:
Nandre Burger, the left arm seamer with rather eye-catching hair, will open the bowling.

de Kock and Mayers out in the middle. Gosh, it looks like a nice day in Johannesburg.

Hello! We're about 5 minutes away now. The ground looks quite full now - for a weekday anyway.

5.15pm We're all set for the start, the ground is filling out nicely. Time to pass over to Danyal Rasool for the opening exchanges.

5.08pm So, here are those teams. Harmer and Paul are the men coming into the fray for DSG

DSG Mayers, Breetzke, de Kock (capt & wk), Mulder, Klaasen, Holder, Paul, Harmer, Viljoen, Maharaj, Topley.

JSK du Plessis (capt), Hendricks, Brand, Makhanya, du Plooy, Ferreira (wk), Shepherd, Burger, Coetzee, Joseph, Maheesh

4.59pm The toss is coming up shortly. Quinton de Kock and Faf du Plessis line up. Faf wins and bowls

"It gets a bit skiddier on the Highveld," he says. "The crowd the whole tournament has been amazing, the Bullring when it's full feels like the stadium is bouncing. When we've been in the contest we've done well, we're getting the smaller things right. Home conditions, four games in a row leading into the knock-outs, is the situation you want."

Nandre Burger comes in for Phangiso, whose action has been reported.

QDK would have bowled first too. "We're desperate for points and no better opportunity than starting tonight. These players are all mature and understand the cause of the team."

Two changes... but Quinnie's mind has gone blank. We'll get clarity shortly.

4.53pmOver in Gqeberha, Paarl Royals have sealed a handy five-wicket win to close the gap to the top. It also opens up a four-point gap between the top and bottom three. All the more incentive for these sides to try to stay in touch with a key win tonight.

4.49pm Afternoon all, welcome to the Wanderers. It's Joburg Super Kings versus DurbanAPOSTROPHEs Super Giants (get it right), and the toss is coming up shortly.

First a quick glance at the table... oh. Fair to say there's room for improvement in the standings for both combatants.

postText:
9.08pm That'll do for tonight, thanks for joining us, from Miller, Danyal and Chandan, good night!

9.03pm Time for the presentations. No prizes for guessing who walked away with the prize... Faf du Plessis is Player of the Match. But first here's De Kock.

"Faf played outstanding tonight, his knowledge and experience showed out. We needed early wickets but still tried, they never gave their wickets away. it's been tough, we fought hard, not going our way."

And here's Faf in his own words. "Important for me to convert those scores, all the leagues I play, I try to get hundreds. Nice wicket, a bit sticky, then typical Wanderers, once you get in... Topley bowled well, Maharaj got the ball to stick, felt we were behind the rate, then got the momentum back. Reeza, I was saying get me on strike, batting is about the partnership, we knew the back-end would be easier. Encouraging him to hit the ball as late as possible. This tournament is unbelievable, so great to play in front of full crowds. The Bullring is on fire!"

8.55pm Well, what a chase that was. Utterly stunning from du Plessis, an innings made all the more extraordinary by the struggle at the other end, where Reeza Hendricks was batting at a tempo four times slower than his skipper. He eventually redeemed his strike-rate towards the end of their hefty 157-run stand, but his departure was some justice for Durban's bowlers. Mayers was effective up top and Topley bowled superbly and without luck. But the rest proved slim pickings.

So, a very important win for Joburg, who have brought themselves back into the chasing pack, on 16 points. Durban are adrift at the foot of the table now, on 8

text: starts off with four! Full and wide outside off stump. Rossington transfers his weight forward and cracks it past cover point
preText:
1:27pm The sun is shining at St. George's Park. The Royals are in a huddle near the boundary rope. Rossington and Hermann, meanwhile, will open the batting for the hosts. Fortuin with the new ball for the Royals. Here we go!

Paarl Royals XI: Jos Buttler (wk), Jason Roy, Wihaan Lubbe, Dane Vilas, David Miller (c), Mitchell van Buuren, Andile Phehlukwayo, Evan Jones, Bjorn Fortuin, Lungi Ngidi, Tabraiz Shamsi

Sunrisers Eastern Cape XI: Adam Rossington (wk), Jordan Hermann, Aiden Markram (c), Tristan Stubbs, Sarel Erwee, JJ Smuts, Marco Jansen, James Fuller, Roelof van der Merwe, Sisanda Magala, Brydon Carse

1pm Time for the toss. And Miller forgets to call the first time. Early drama! Miller calls but wrongly this time. The Sunrisers Eastern Cape will bat first. One change for the Sunrisers - Mason Crane is out. Miller says he would have bowled first anyway. Miller reckons it is going to be a good wicket. One change for the Royals too, with Andile Phehlukwayo coming into the side. We will bring the playing XIs to you shortly!

12:35pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of this SA20 clash between the Paarl Royals and the Sunrisers Eastern Cape. I am Shashwat Kumar and I will be your eyes and ears for everything that happens today in this potentially fascinating contest.

Both teams come into this game having won their most recent encounter. While the Royals got the better of table-toppers Pretoria Capitals on Sunday, the Sunrisers routed Durban's Super Giants by 124 runs on the same day. The Sunrisers, in fact, have won four of their last five matches and could solidify second spot with another victory today. The Royals, meanwhile, currently sit third on the points table and would want to go level with the Sunrisers (at the very least; a bonus point will take them above today's opponents).

So, there is plenty riding on this contest. Both teams, including today, have only three fixtures left, meaning that they have to be on their toes and ensure that they are still part of the knockout phase when it comes along. Lots of stars on display too, and despite this contest being staged in the afternoon, there should be enough star quality in the game to keep you glued to your television screens.

postText:
3:08pm A rather underwhelming innings by the Sunrisers. The pitch was not very conducive to stroke-play but the hosts never got going. They only scored 30 runs in the powerplay and despite Smuts' best efforts, never looked likely of breaching the 140-run mark. In fact, had Smuts not managed a 49-ball 65, things could have been even more dire for the Sunrisers.

Credit must also be given to the Royals. They did not offer much room to the batters and stuck to their plans. Their ploy to bowl into the surface and take the pace off also worked wonders. Despite the surface being slightly tricky, the Royals will back themselves to chase this down. Talk of a bonus point might be too premature at this stage but there is no denying that the visitors are the happier of the two outfits at the break. Do join us in a bit for the run-chase!

Andile Phehlukwayo: (On playing his first game) It was unbelievable. Good to get an opportunity to play. It has been a while and it was a long time coming. It is a score we back ourselves to chase. (On the pitch) The track is not that easy to bat on. It is a used wicket and we have to be smart about how we play. The wind is also a big factor.

text: oh dear! Short and wide outside off stump. Carse lets it go and the umpire calls it a wide. The non-striker, for some reason, scampers across for a bye and for a moment, both are at the same end. Buttler fires it to the bowler, who fumbles and then misses his shy at the stumps. Two runs added to the total in the end, and one ball is still left in the innings!

postText:
4:55pm Right. That will be a wrap from us for this game. The action, though, does not stop. In about half an hour, Durban's Super Giants will clash swords with the Joburg Super Kings. Do join us for that game too but until next time, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of Chandan. Goodbye, and take care!

4:53pm Phew, that was a game that was filled with twists and turns at every juncture. In the end, though, the Royals did just enough to hold their nerve. Buttler set up the run-chase with a blistering powerplay. The middle overs were more of a struggle, with the spinners in particular, tightening the screw. Miller, however, kept his cool at the end and did what he does best - finish off the game.

The Sunrisers, meanwhile, would be left ruing what could have been had they put up more runs on the board. Their bowling plans, especially in the 18th over, also left a bit to be desired, considering Magala kept venturing into Miller's arc. That said, they are still comfortably placed on the points table, and when the SA20 resumes after the ODI series between England and South Africa, they will have their fate in their own hands.

preText:
5:28pm The sun is out, and the players are out in the middle too. Jacks and Mendis to open the batting for the Capitals. Linde with the new ball. Here we go!

Pretoria Capitals XI: Kusal Mendis (wk), Will Jacks, Theunis de Bruyn, Rilee Rossouw, James Neesham, Clyde Fortuin, Eathan Bosch, Wayne Parnell (c), Senuran Muthusamy, Adil Rashid, Anrich Nortje

MI Cape Town XI: Ryan Rickelton, Dewald Brevis, Sam Curran, Grant Roelofsen (wk), Rassie van der Dussen, George Linde, Delano Potgieter, Odean Smith, Rashid Khan (c), Jofra Archer, Kagiso Rabada

5pm It's time for the toss. Rashid Khan gives the coin a spin and it lands in his favour. MI Cape Town will bowl first. He says batting gets a little easier under lights. No changes for MI Cape Town. Parnell admits he would have bowled first too but he is not very unhappy about batting first. One change for the Capitals - Dadswell is out. We will bring the playing XIs to you shortly.

MI Cape Town have struggled a little with the bat so far, registering only one score in excess of 160. They have also batted first on four occasions and have won only once, indicating that they rely on their strong bowling unit to set up games. The Capitals, meanwhile, have looked a more well-rounded outfit, with Jacks and Salt in terrific form at the top of the order, and Nortje breathing fire with the ball. All these and many more intriguing sub-plots await tonight, and this could morph into a game that helps one of these two sides take a definitive step towards qualification.

4:35pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of the SA20. Tonight, MI Cape Town will be taking on the Pretoria Capitals in a game that promises to be very fascinating. The Capitals currently sit atop the points table. MI Cape Town, meanwhile, are third and snapped their two-match losing streak on Saturday against the Paarl Royals. Plenty to play for, like always, and I (Shashwat) will be bringing to you everything that happens in this contest. Sit back, relax and enjoy!

lovely! Flighted on a full length on leg stump. Mendis gives himself a bit of room and caresses it over extra cover
full delivery on leg stump. Mendis walks across his stumps and paddles it straight to short fine leg
fuller and slightly down the leg side. Mendis gets some bat on it and this time, gets it past short fine leg too
flies for six! Full and slanted into the pads. Mendis gets down on one knee and heaves it over the deep square leg fence!
back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. Mendis gets onto the back foot and taps it towards backward point
four more! Short and wide outside off stump. Mendis has all the time in the world to rock back and thread it past cover point
back of a length delivery outside off stump. Jacks lets the ball come to him before meeting it right under his eyes
preText: Archer into the attack. Can he prize out an opening?

text: back of a length delivery on off stump that holds up a little. Jacks gets up on his toes and plonks it into the on side
back of a length delivery just outside off stump that climbs up on the batter. Jacks accounts for it well enough and drops it into the off side

back of a length delivery outside off stump. Jacks gets on top of the bounce and punches it towards cover point. The fielder stops it excellently but the fielder at backward point then fires an errant throw and allows the second
beautiful! In the slot outside off stump and Jacks cashes in! He plants his front foot and crashes it over extra cover

oh wow! Contender for shot of the tournament! Back of a length delivery at the stumps. Jacks picks up the length early, stands up tall like Virat Kohli did at the MCG against Haris Rauf, and dumps it into the sightscreen!
slower delivery on a length outside off stump. Mendis has an ugly swipe at it and misses the ball by quite some distance
preText: Garett : "Is Phil Salt being rested or did he pick up a niggle? In cracking good form....." -- He is ill and was not available for today

text: full delivery on middle and off stump. Mendis has a stab at it and chunks it off the inside edge towards deep square leg
back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. Jacks gets up on his toes and defends into the off side
power! Short, wide and punished! Too much width and it allows Jacks to throw his hands at it and blister it over extra cover
four more! Full toss outside off stump. Jacks uses the pace on offer, opens his bat face and steers it past short third man
another majestic maximum! Back of a length delivery on middle and leg stump. Jacks opens up his stance and pumps it over long on! He hit that with almost a straight blade, simply stunning!
full delivery angled into the batter on middle and leg stump. Mendis hangs back and tips it down the ground before haring across to the other end
palms it over the bar! Banged into the track outside off stump. Jacks absolutely laces it towards deep square leg, where the fielder palms it over the fence
very full delivery on leg stump. Jacks jams his bat down on it and digs it out towards the bowler
this is just ridiculous! Back of a length delivery outside off stump that sits up to be hit. Jacks stands tall and forehands it over the long off fence! Brings up his fifty too, off just 19 balls!
sharp bumper on leg stump. Jacks has a swing at it but misses. The umpire, though, deems it high enough to be called a wide
full delivery on middle and leg stump. Jacks plants his front foot and flicks it over mid wicket. The ball plugs in the outfield, meaning that Jacks only gets two runs
very full delivery on middle and leg stump. Jacks drives it back to the bowler, who gets his right boot in the way
postText: Wow, that was a whirlwind powerplay and MI Cape Town, more than the Capitals, need this breather. 84 runs in six overs, and Jacks looks like he can hit boundaries anywhere and everywhere on the field. The hosts need wickets, and they need them pretty quickly after the time-out

text: length delivery just outside off stump. Mendis goes back and drops it into the off side for a sharp single
preText: This is also the highest powerplay score at this year's SA20. Can Rashid put a lid on the run-scoring now?

text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. Jacks rocks onto the back foot and pulls it away towards deep mid wicket for one

shortText: Rashid Khan to Mendis, no run
text: googly on a back of a length on off stump. Mendis goes back and dabs it down to short third man
back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. Mendis gets onto the back foot and swings it away towards deep mid wicket
shorter on off stump. Jacks camps deep in his crease and pulls it towards deep mid wicket for another run

wkt_text: BKG Mendis c Linde b Rashid Khan 29 (35m 19b 4x4 1x6) SR: 152.63
text: superb work on the fence, finally! Back of a length delivery on off stump that seems to hurry onto the batter. Mendis has a swipe at it but clogs it a touch. Rickelton judges the catch to perfection at deep mid wicket, takes it at the first go and then flicks it back to Linde as soon as he realises that he will step onto the boundary cushion! But has he managed to do so? The third umpire is having multiple looks at it before agreeing that the fielder has pulled it off successfully!
short and outside off stump. Jacks waits in his crease and short-arm jabs it towards deep mid wicket for a single
preText: Rossouw in at 3. But he is at the non-striker's end for now. Odean Smith into the attack

text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. Rossouw gets up on his toes and dabs it towards deep cover point for one
back of a length delivery on leg stump. Jacks gives himself a bit of room but guides it straight to the fielder at short third man
shot! Short, wide and punished! Too much width and all Jacks has to do is hold his shot long enough and knife it past backward point

wkt_text: WG Jacks c †Roelofsen b Smith 62 (39m 27b 5x4 5x6) SR: 229.62
text: edged and taken! Back of a length delivery in the channel that might have nipped away ever so slightly. Jacks has a nibble at it without much foot movement and gets a feather through to the keeper. Smith is over the moon; Jacks is not very pleased with his stroke. Massive moment in the game!

shortText: Smith to de Bruyn, no run
text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn gets up on his toes and defends into the off side
preText: de Bruyn is the new man in

shortText: Rashid Khan to Rossouw, no run
text: length delivery on leg stump. Rossouw has a prod at it and misses as the ball strikes him on the pads
preText: Rashid to bowl his second

shortText: Rashid Khan to Rossouw, no run
text: googly on a back of a length outside off stump. Rossouw does not pick it at all and misses his shot altogether

shortText: Rashid Khan to Rossouw, no run
text: length delivery just outside off stump. Rossouw brings out the reverse paddle but can't beat short third man

wkt_text: RR Rossouw lbw b Rashid Khan 1 (10m 5b 0x4 0x6) SR: 20.00
text: Rashid gets Rossouw! Length delivery on middle and off stump that skids through. It looks like Rossouw has not picked it again and goes back to a ball he should have been forward to. He is nowhere close to the ball in the end as the ball smashes into the pads in front of middle and off stump. The umpire raises his finger, and Rossouw does not even bother with the review! That looked plumb!
length delivery on off stump. Muthusamy goes back and works it into the leg side for a single
preText: Muthusamy joins de Bruyn. Both batters on nought

shortText: Rashid Khan to de Bruyn, 1 run
text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn reads it off the surface and knocks it down the ground for one
preText: Slip in place for de Bruyn

shortText: Archer to de Bruyn, no run
text: back of a length delivery just outside off stump. de Bruyn gets onto the back foot and pats it towards backward point
preText: Sam: "Is the pitch a belter, or was it just tremendous batting from the openers? Did Jacks do what Rossington did yesterday by making a tricky pitch look great?" -- A bit of both, to be honest. The pitch is a lot truer than we have usually seen this season. But take nothing away from what was a truly special innings by Jacks

text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn goes back and stabs it towards mid wicket for a single
length delivery on middle and off stump that keeps a tad low. Muthusamy is caught on the crease and somehow clinks it back to the bowler
full delivery outside off stump. Muthusamy comes forward and drives it neatly towards deep cover point for a couple of runs
preText: Around the wicket now

text: banged into the track outside off stump. Muthusamy has a half-hearted swish at it and makes absolutely no contact

wkt_text: S Muthusamy c †Roelofsen b Archer 3 (9m 4b 0x4 0x6) SR: 75.00
text: what a ripper! And Archer brings out the Marcus Rashford (and Bukayo Saka from yesterday) celebration too! Length delivery angled into the batter on off stump. On pitching, though, this one snakes away and squares up the batter completely. Muthusamy dangles his bat out, more in hope than anything, and ends up feathering it through to the keeper!
length delivery just outside off stump. Fortuin comes half forward and prods it into the off side
preText: Clyde Fortuin walks out to the middle, with the Capitals in a spot of bother

text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn goes back and pushes it towards deep cover point
preText:
Back to the cricket now. Linde into the attack

Jack: "What does this celebration from Archer signify ?" -- It is basically a celebration where he points to his head. Rashford has been doing it for a while now, and Saka did it yesterday after scoring for Arsenal against Rashford's Manchester United

text: tossed up on a length outside off stump. Fortuin lunges forward and nudges it towards deep point. Fortuin then decides he wants to hare back for the second and this looks a close call as the fielder fires in an accurate throw and the keeper whips off the bails. Replays, though, confirm that Fortuin had made his ground relatively comfortably
length delivery outside off stump. Fortuin presses half forward and jabs it towards backward point
full delivery on leg stump. Fortuin comes forward and flicks it down the ground towards long on for a single
tossed up on a length on leg stump. de Bruyn backs away a shade and chips it towards long off for a couple of runs
back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn waits in his crease, and threads it past backward point and short third man for a much-needed boundary!
short delivery outside off stump. Fortuin throws his hands at it and flashes it down to third man for a single
short delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn gets onto the back foot and pulls it towards deep mid wicket for one
short and wide outside off stump. Fortuin hops up onto his toes, fetches it and muscles it past mid on. The fielder comes around from deep mid wicket and saves the boundary

shortText: Smith to de Bruyn, 1 leg bye
text: huge appeal, not given! Back of a length delivery on off stump. de Bruyn shuffles across his stumps and then plays all around it as the ball thuds into the pads. Rashid deliberates but decides against the review
slower delivery on a back of a length on off stump. Fortuin waits for the ball to arrive before tapping it into the off side
back of a length delivery angled into the batter on middle and leg stump. Fortuin again plays all over it as the ball pings into the thigh pad

shortText: Rashid Khan to de Bruyn, no run
text: back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. de Bruyn hangs back and stabs it towards extra cover

shortText: Rashid Khan to de Bruyn, 1 run
text: back of a length delivery on off stump. de Bruyn is a little late on the pull and clogs it towards long on for a single
length delivery on middle and off stump. Fortuin goes deep into his crease and jabs it into the off side for one

shortText: Rashid Khan to de Bruyn, 1 run
text: googly on a length on off stump. de Bruyn does not quite pick the googly and squirts it off the inside edge into the on side for one
preText: James Iyer: "Rashid now has 499 t20 wickets" -- Yes, and he is still only 24

text: full delivery on leg stump. Fortuin lunges forward and helps it round the corner for another run

shortText: Rashid Khan to de Bruyn, 1 run
text: full delivery on off stump. de Bruyn closes his bat face slightly early and gets a leading edge into the off side
length delivery just outside off stump. de Bruyn backs away and drives it on the up towards deep cover point for a single
slower delivery on a back of a length outside off stump. Fortuin is early into his stroke and scuffs it towards extra cover for one

shortText: Smith to de Bruyn, no run
text: wayward short delivery outside off stump. Left alone by de Bruyn, and called a wide by the umpire
back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn gets on top of the bounce and punches it towards deep cover point for a single
full delivery just outside off stump. Fortuin has a wild slog at it and inside edges it onto his pads
de Bruyn makes Smith pay! Right in the slot outside off stump. de Bruyn plants his front foot and mauls it over the wide long on fence
preText: Free hit coming up. de Bruyn on strike

text: full and angled into middle and leg stump. Fortuin backs away and knocks it down the ground for a single. Oh hang, on! Looks like Smith has overstepped here!

wkt_text: C Fortuin  b Rashid Khan 11 (24m 14b 0x4 0x6) SR: 78.57
text: 500 T20 wickets for Rashid! Full and outside off stump. Fortuin, who has been feeling the pinch in the last few overs, has another wild hack at it. But he swings too hard and is nowhere close to the pitch of the ball either. He ends up dragging it onto his stumps. Take a bow, Rashid Khan!
preText: Rashid to bowl out

shortText: Rashid Khan to Neesham, no run
text: length delivery on leg stump. Neesham brings out the reverse sweep first up, and the ball pops up off the pads into no man's land. Did that hit the bat as well?
preText: Neesham in at 7. Will he play Rashid out, or will be try to counter-attack?

shortText: Rashid Khan to Neesham, no run
text: googly on a length just outside off stump. Neesham comes half forward and dabs it towards first slip
gets it away! Full delivery on leg stump. Neesham gets down on one knee, gets inside the line and helps it past short fine leg
short and outside leg stump. Neesham waits in his crease and heaves it towards deep backward square leg

shortText: Rashid Khan to de Bruyn, no run
text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn gets onto the back foot and blocks it towards extra cover
back of a length delivery just outside off stump. Neesham gets up on his toes and taps it gently towards backward point
preText:
Archer to bowl the 16th

Asahel: "500 wickets at the age of 24! This when teams all around the world mostly look to play him out. What a talent!"

text: back of a length delivery outside off stump. Neesham runs it down to third man and collects a single
slower delivery on a full length on middle and off stump. de Bruyn hangs back and works it towards deep mid wicket for one
back of a length delivery outside off stump that zips through. Neesham has a fish at it but is beaten by the extra pace and bounce. Lucky to not get a scratch on that!
full delivery on middle and off stump. Neesham lets the ball come to him before tucking it off his toes for one
shot! Slower delivery on a length just outside off stump. de Bruyn backs away, picks the variation and pumps it over mid off
short and at the batter on middle and leg stump. de Bruyn has a swing at it but misses. Called a wide for height, though
length outside off stump. Neesham throws his hands at it and laces it towards deep cover point for a single
preText: Rabada returns. He has given away 32 runs in two overs already today

text: safe! Slower bumper way outside off stump. de Bruyn has to reach out for it but he mistimes it so badly that it lands well in front of long on
yorker outside off stump. Neesham dabs it towards the keeper, who dives and saves a few runs. Can't prevent a sharp single, however

shortText: Rabada to de Bruyn, no run
text: slower delivery on a length outside off stump. de Bruyn has a massive swish at it but is early into the stroke. Only connects with thin air
full delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn sits deep in his crease and drills it back past the bowler. Long on comes around and cuts it off, albeit with a little help from his pal at long off
slower bumper outside off stump. de Bruyn walks across and looks to access the leg side but can only glove it into the on side for a single
shot! Full delivery outside off stump. de Bruyn walks across his stumps and scoops it delightfully over short fine leg
preText: Archer to bowl out

wkt_text: TB de Bruyn c Brevis b Archer 36 (50m 26b 2x4 2x6) SR: 138.46
text: picks out short fine leg to perfection! Another very full delivery outside off stump, and de Bruyn looks to repeat the stroke. This time, though, he cramps himself for room a touch and the fullness means he can't quite get under it. He arrows it straight to short fine leg, who makes no mistake!
angled into the stumps. Parnell gets forward and pokes it down the ground to get off the mark
preText: Parnell comes out to bat

text: high full toss on off stump. Neesham uses the pace and dabs it down to short third man. That was perilously close to being called a No ball

wkt_text: WD Parnell c Potgieter b Archer 1 (4m 2b 0x4 0x6) SR: 50.00
text: Archer gets another! Slower delivery dug into the track on leg stump. Parnell looks to get inside the line and help it past short fine leg but ends up hitting it straight down the fielder's throat! MI Cape Town continue to chip away at the wickets!
what a shot! Full delivery outside off stump. Bosch leans into his drive and caresses it between short extra cover and mid off
banged into the track outside off stump. Bosch has a stab at it and misses. Luckily for him, the umpire deems it high enough to be called a wide
preText: Bosch to try his luck now

text: full delivery outside off stump. Neesham plants his front foot and powers it down the ground for a siingle
preText: Sam: "The last ball of an extra hurting MI CT with Smith and Archer going for sixes there" -- Add a boundary to that list now. Can the Capitals get up to 190 here?

text: back of a length delivery at the stumps. Bosch has a hack at it and misses as the ball deflects off the thigh pad towards short third man
bumper on middle and leg stump. Neesham decides that he wants to duck underneath it and does so. Slightly perplexing, though, considering the circumstances
short and outside off stump. Neesham reaches out for it and toe-ends it towards long on. However, he is alert enough to scamper back for the second
breaks the shackles! Low full toss way outside off stump. Neesham throws his hands at it and flays it over backward point
two fours in a row! Full toss outside off stump again. Neesham opens up his stance and muscles it past deep mid wicket for another boundary!
slower delivery on a length outside off stump. Bosch picks the slower one and drills it down the ground towards long off for three more runs. Excellent effort by Archer on the fence!
preText: One over left. 176 on the board already. Will the Capitals get to 190? Smith to bowl the final over of the innings

text: full delivery outside off stump. Neesham comes onto the front foot and lasers it back down the ground. Rabada, though, hares around at long off and cuts it off
short delivery outside off stump that skids through. Bosch has a massive swipe at it but only connects with fresh air

wkt_text: E Bosch c Rickelton b Smith 7 (12m 5b 1x4 0x6) SR: 140.00
text: Bosch bites the dust! Slower delivery on a back of a length outside off stump. Bosch continues swinging but he is again too early into the stroke. The ball skews up off the outside edge and swirls towards backward point. Rickelton calls early and completes the catch!
slower bumper outside off stump. Rashid does not pick it till very late and dabs it past backward point for a single
preText: Adil Rashid in at 10. 190 is looking very distant now, unless Adil Rashid has something up his sleeve

text: length delivery outside off stump that shapes away a touch. Brevis comes half forward and taps it gently towards backward point
preText: 7:29pm We are back. 183 to chase. Brevis and Rickelton to open the batting. Bosch with the ball for the Capitals. Let's go!

text: full delivery outside off stump that leaves the batter late. Brevis throws his hands at it but gets nowhere close to the ball
back of a length delivery outside off stump. Rickelton gets up on his toes and defends it towards backward point
length delivery fired down the leg side. The keeper can't collect cleanly and allows a bye as well
slower delivery on a length just outside off stump. Rickelton comes onto the front foot again and pats it gently towards backward point
back of a length delivery on middle and leg stump. Rickelton gets up on his toes and pushes it towards mid on
shot! Full delivery just outside off stump. Rickelton leans into the drive and effortlessly threads it past mid off for four
and he is welcomed with a boundary! Back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. Brevis marches down the track and bangs it over the bowler's head
preText: Parnell to share the new ball

text: full delivery outside off stump. Brevis comes forward and digs it out towards cover point
back of a length delivery outside off stump. Brevis gets up on his toes and works it down the ground for another single
back of a length delivery just outside off stump. Rickelton hops up onto his toes and jabs it into the off side
full delivery just outside off stump. Rickelton gets onto the front foot and laces it straight to mid off
slower delivery on a length just outside off stump. Rickelton tips it down the ground and scampers across to the other end
half-tracker on middle and leg stump. Rickelton gets inside the line of the ball and helps it neatly past short fine leg for four
safe! Length delivery just outside off stump. Rickelton has a swing at it and clogs it badly. Luckily for him, it just evades Parnell at mid on
back of a length delivery outside off stump. Rickelton is early into his stroke again and clunks it back to the bowler

wkt_text: RD Rickelton c sub (M Pretorius) b Bosch 11 (11b 2x4 0x6) SR: 100.00
text: soft dismissal! Back of a length delivery angled across outside off stump. Rickelton looks to work to leg but because the ball sticks in the surface, he ends up getting a tame leading edge that nestles into mid off's palms! Just the wicket the Capitals needed inside the powerplay!
back of a length delivery just outside off stump. Curran runs it down to third man and gets off the mark
preText: Curran in at 3

text: slower delivery on a back of a length on leg stump. Brevis helps it behind square on the leg side for one more run
banged into the track outside off stump. Brevis gets onto the back foot and tugs it towards deep square leg for a single
back of a length delivery on off stump. Curran gets up on his toes and punches it towards extra cover
back of a length delivery angled into middle and leg stump. Curran gives himself a bit of room and cuts it towards cover point
back of a length delivery just outside off stump. Curran gets up on his toes and drops it into the off side
breaks the shackles! Dug into the track on middle and leg stump. Curran backs away very early and slaps it over extra cover

huge appeal, not given! Full and darted into the stumps. Curran is hanging back in his crease and has a hurried stab at it. He seems to miss it as the ball thuds into the pads. Parnell reviews. Replays indicate that Curran has not hit it. But is it sliding down leg? Yes, it is! Curran survives!
back of a length delivery just outside off stump. Brevis gets behind the line of the ball and presents the full face of the bat
preText: Right then. Nortje into the attack. Can he break this game open?

text: back of a length delivery on middle and leg stump. Brevis goes back and tucks it off his hips towards deep square leg for a single
jaffa! Back of a length delivery in the channel that jags away sharply. Curran hangs his bat out and is beaten all ends up
back of a length delivery on middle and leg stump. Curran gets onto the back foot and prods it into the off side
banged into the track at the batter on leg stump. Curran ducks underneath it, and the umpire reckons it is not high enough to be called a wide
another sharp bumper on off stump. Curran ducks underneath it again
full and slanted into off stump. Brevis walks across his stumps, uses the angle and clips it through the backward square leg region for four
preText: Bosch to round off the powerplay

text: four more! Slower delivery on a shortish length outside off stump. Brevis waits for the ball to arrive before throwing his hands at it. The ball whistles off the willow and hurtles past cover point
back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. Brevis goes back and punches it towards mid wicket for one
right out of the screws! Back of a length delivery on off stump that sits up to be hit! He clears his front leg and whacks it over cow corner
back of a length delivery on middle and off stump. Curran pushes it into the off side and collects another single
short delivery outside off stump. Brevis has a hack at it but is late on the stroke as the ball whizzes past the flailing bat
back of a length delivery on middle and leg stump. Curran hops up onto his toes and blocks it back to the bowler
preText: Nortje to continue

text: back of a length delivery just outside off stump. Curran shuffles across and looks to help it over short fine leg. He gets into an awful tangle, though, and cops a blow on the body for his toil
just short! Banged into the track on off stump. Brevis takes his eyes off it completely and has a swing at it. The ball skews off the top edge but lands just in front of deep square leg
or maybe they are now! Short and outside off stump. This one sits up to be hit and Curran is good enough to smash it over mid wicket
preText: The MI Cape Town batters are not fancying Nortje's raw pace here

text: back of a length delivery on off stump. Curran tips it into the off side and scrambles across to the other end. Curran had to dive to make his ground and was also saved by Rossouw missing his shy at the bowler's end
dug into the track outside off stump. Brevis has a long, hard look at it before letting the ball go through to the keeper
slider on a back of a length on middle and off stump. Curran rocks onto the back foot and bisects the gap between deep mid wicket and long on with a scorching pull shot!
preText: Adil Rashid into the attack now. The required run-rate is just over 10, as things stand

wkt_text: SM Curran  b Rashid 22 (18b 3x4 1x6) SR: 122.22
text: knocks him over with an absolute peach! Given a bit of air on a length just outside off stump. Curran thinks he has enough width to work with and is shaping for the cut. The ball, though, pitches and spins back a mile, going past Curran's flailing bat and crashing into the stumps! Curran can't quite believe what has happened but he has to walk back!
short and way outside off stump. Curran thinks about playing at it before leaving it well alone. Called a wide

shortText: Rashid to van der Dussen, 1 run
text: short and outside off stump. van der Dussen reaches out for it and drags it into the leg side for a single
preText: van der Dussen in at 4

text: length delivery angled into leg stump. Brevis backs away but ends up tapping it back to the bowler
just clears long off! Flighted on a length outside off stump. Brevis gives it the lot but does not quite middle it. The ball goes miles up in the air and just clears the fielder at long off
six more! Another drag-down on middle and leg stump. This one does not bounce as much but Brevis does not care one bit! He rocks back and slams it over long on

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, no run
text: length delivery just outside off stump. van der Dussen comes half forward and pokes it towards short extra cover
preText: Neesham into the attack

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, no run

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, 1 run
text: back of a length delivery on off stump. van der Dussen turns it into the on side and collects a single
back of a length delivery on leg stump. Brevis glances it behind square on the leg side for one

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, no run
text: back of a length delivery on off stump that decks back. van der Dussen is cut in half and is bewildered how Neesham was able to extract that sort of movement

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, 1 run
text: length delivery just outside off stump. van der Dussen comes forward and pushes it down the ground for a single

shortText: Rashid to van der Dussen, 1 run
text: full delivery on off stump. van der Dussen lunges forward and prods it down the ground for a single
preText: Rashid to continue after the time-out

text: oh dear! Flighted on a full length on leg stump. Brevis backs away and drags it down to long on. He is intent on the second but van der Dussen is not. Fortunately for Brevis, Rashid can't gather cleanly at the bowler's end

shortText: Rashid to van der Dussen, no run
text: quicker and flatter on a length on leg stump. van der Dussen pulls it straight to short fine leg

shortText: Rashid to van der Dussen, 1 run
text: full delivery on middle and leg stump. van der Dussen stretches out and knocks it down the ground for one
length delivery on leg stump. Brevis waits in his crease and helps it round the corner for another single

shortText: Rashid to van der Dussen, no run
text: slider on a length on middle and off stump. van der Dussen does not quite pick it and ends up shanking it back to the bowler
full and slanted into the batter's pads. Brevis backs away further and flicks it towards deep square leg
preText: MI Cape Town are slightly behind the game at the half-way mark but they still have eight wickets in hand. If Brevis can click into overdrive, and if van der Dussen can find his groove, they will be in with more than a shout. The Capitals need a wicket or two to feel comfortable

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, no run
text: slower delivery on a back of a length outside off stump. van der Dussen has a massive mow across the line but makes no contact whatsoever

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, 1 run
text: dug into the track on off stump. van der Dussen shuffles across and pulls it away towards fine leg for just a single
back of a length delivery on off stump. Brevis is slightly early on the pull and drags it towards deep square leg

shortText: Neesham to van der Dussen, 3 runs

preText:
Oh, well. Here is a surprise. Jacks to bowl the 15th over. This could either be an inspired call, or a questionable one. We will find out soon!

Right. All to play for in the six overs that remain. MI Cape Town would have ideally wanted Brevis at the crease but this pair is capable of inflicting plenty of damage. The Capitals only have one over of Nortje left, and it would be interesting to see how and where they use him. 73 runs needed off 36 balls.

postText:
9:17pm Right. That will be a wrap from us for this game. It promised so much, especially at the half-way stage but soon meandered towards a one-sided contest, although that was down to how clinical the Capitals were. Tomorrow, the Paarl Royals will be in action and they will clash against the Sunrisers Eastern Cape, currently placed second and hoping to keep pace with the Capitals. Until next time, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of everyone at ESPNcricinfo! Goodbye, goodnight and take care!

9:14pm A fairly comfortable victory for the Capitals in the end. MI Cape Town never really got going and the only time they looked to be in the contest in the second innings was when Brevis was at the crease. Once the youngster departed, van der Dussen could not take up the mantle and his 25-ball 24 did their chances more harm than good. The rest of the middle order also looked thin, and with the likes of Nortje and Parnell firing on all cylinders, MI Cape Town were, quite frankly, blown away.

Parnell also deserves plenty of praise for how he handled his resources. The gamble to bring Jacks on worked a charm, as did the ploy to persist with Rashid, despite him conceding 18 runs in his opening over. The Capitals, in short, won all the moments that mattered tonight and now sit comfortably atop the points table.

text: Yorker around off, blocked in front. No first-ball wicket for Mayers, swung it in well.
preText:
Mayers will start with no slip.

5:27pm: Eventually, it's Paul, Breetzke, and Dhananjaya who are in for Sunrisers. Super Giants disperse from their huddle with clouds in the stadium's background. The floodlights are on. Rossington will open with Hermann.

Here are the Playing XIs of both teams.

5:10pm: Royals have completed the win at Paarl. David Miller was able to latch onto Anrich Nortje's bowling in the last over failing two overs prior. Mitchell Van Buuren played second fiddle.

Pitch: Pommie Mbangwa says the pitch has had a sprinkle and a roll, same surface as yesterday which had twenty of the 40 overs of spin. Shaun Pollock adds non-big-turners like Aaron Phangiso, Maheesh Theekshana got turn yesterday. So it'd be an examination by spin. The questions he poses for batters are around planing the attack and bring out the sweep. Ashwell Prince says learning to adapt is important in varying conditions across South Africa. Hitting length balls over the top is hard due to the lack of pace. Says the ball needs to be close to the bat to be successful.

Quinton de Kock says they were unsure. Says they'll bat second to know what'll be needed on the wicket. He watched bit of yesterday's game, noticed turn in the wicket. Says Lance Klusner, the coach, pumped them up after the last game; that they need to get the mindset ready and carry on. Couple of changes. Aiden Markram says they would have liked to chase as well as it'd (pitch) be even at night. Says they need more application is needed with the bat and that it's hard to put a number on the total. 145, 150+ would be good. Mason Crane in, Brydon Carse out.

5:03pm: Durban Super Giants win the toss and bowl

4:45pm: *Inhales deeply* Do you smell that? *A couple smaller inhales* It's the fragrance of sweet old cricket. The T20-league carnivàle has us set to entertain all the time from around the globe. The SA20 is among the gifts that keep on giving, it's doing so right now as hosts Paarl Royals look to close out a tricky 159-run chase, they need 32 off 23. Follow the action here. Right after that's done, it'll be toss time in Gqeberha as Sunrisers Eastern Cape take on Durban's Super Giants. Welcome aboard.

text: Fetch that! Where is the ball gone? Into orbit. "New ball please," screams Pommie Mbangwa on air. Gets a length ball outside off, Stubbs always is in position, having moved across to off. He just extends his arms and smashes it welll over long-on.
Wide yorker outside off, manages to flick it through midwicket.
Full and wide outside off, he moves across and clips it to long-on.
Goes deep in his crease as he moves to the off side, but only squeezes this full ball to long-on.
Clever, clever shot. Markram was still till the point Mulder let it off his hands. And then, he quickly hops to play the cheeky reverse scoop well past short third to the low full toss outside off.
Very full on the pads, he misses the flick and wears it on his back leg.
preText: Holder to close the innings.

text: Very full on leg, he whips it to deep square leg and sprints back for two.
Very full on middle and leg, flicks it through midwicket and yet again hares back for two.
Once again Holder bowls it to his field - full and straight on leg - but Stubbs manages to flick it to the longer part at deep midwicket for a couple. Raises the 200 for Sunrisers.
Audacious! Improvisation at its best. Holder goes short around leg. Stubbs quickly turns the bat in his hands, jumps and whacks it over short third. It goes the distance.
Stubbs ends it on a high! Full on middle and leg, he nonchalantly flicks it through midwicket for four. 16 off the final over, Sunrisers finish at 210 for 2!
postText:
Super Giants have their tasks cut out. Back shortly for the run chase.

Adam Rossington: "We knew that powerplay was going to be crucial. It skidded more today than yesterday. With the rain around, I think we have enough. Thrilled to be part of SA20. They've got some dangerous players. We have got to win the powerplay and go from there."

7:37pm Sixty runs off the last five overs, Sunrisers have had a perfect finish, despite the rain break. If it was Rossington who provided the fireworks at the start, with a 30-ball blitz for 72, it was the young-gun Stubbs, who made 27 off just 13, that helped Sunrisers rocket past the 200 mark. It was not meant to be a quick, run-scoring track but Sunrisers have done exactly the opposite.

text: Back of length, turns in from around off. Beats the flick, Mayers was searching. Hits pad, goes towards cover.
preText:
Smuts to Mayers. Around.

7:50pm: Welcome back. Weather's okay now, players walk out. Matthew Breetzke is up at the top.

text: Blocks the length ball back in front.
Fullish ball on leg, bunted to the leg side. Looked like square leg.
Full ball just outside off, driven straight. Long-on keeps it to one.
Length on middle and off, the 91 kph ball got decent bounce and was patted to mid-on
Down the pitch, makes room and slashes the full ball to long-off
postText: Fruit salad over, lots of mix-ups in lengths. Good start in both innings for Sunrisers.

text: Back of length at the stumps, clipped to square leg.
Length, slightly back maybe, at 96 kph just outside off. Breetzke reaches as he defends this back to the bowler.

Misfield at square leg allows one. Was a flighted ball that was flicked to the left of the fielder.

wkt_text: MP Breetzke  b Markram 3 (7b 0x4 0x6) SR: 42.85

Length around off, driven square to point
Back of length just outside off at 96 kph, driven to point.

Full outside off, driven to long-on
Full on leg, clipped to deep square. Effectively a yorker, darting it like spinners do in T20s.
Drags it across with a sweep. Tried slogging the 94 kph ball, not off the middle but went along the ground and fast

text: LBW appeal upheld right away, Mayers reviews! Fair ball. Was fullish, pitching around leg (is it outside?), spun away. Went past the sweep on one knee and hit him in front. Ball-tracking shows it's pitching just outside leg. Mayers survives.
Lands wide on a length and turns away big, close to the tramline. Reaches out and tries cutting, underedges it into the pitch
Fullish ball spins away to middle, blocked to the off side.
Length outside off, beaten on the cut. Looked to have turned away
Back of length outside off at 84 kph, square driven off the back foot to point
Flat on a length at 87 kph on off, blocked to cover.
postText: Maiden. Over-rate must be through the roof. Spinners are going through overs real fast. Getting great purchase too.

text: Doesn't start well, offers width. Short enough to caress a cut along the ground, through the gap at point. 126 kph
preText: Magala will replace spin, he's been great so far in the tournament but how will he do in these conditions?

text: Similar ball, driven again. With the swing. Deep-backward point runs across and stops it.
Full around off, driven to mid-off
Overpitched on middle, stays leg side and drives to mid-off. Middled but scooted straight to the fielder.

Banged in, banged away with the pull. To the short boundary at midwicket. Was outside off, didn't rise much, where did it land? It's like a pitch-perfect yorker. Looked like there was a patch of grass in line with the cushions on either side of the toblerone on which the ball went. Third umpire calls it six after multiple views.
Full just outside off, driven on the rise. Through extra, stopped in the deep.

Launched from wide, has to drag it straight. Doesn't middle it, but gets it over mid-on, who runs back. Can't get to it, landed in the outfield and went for four. It was like a flick across, Mulder's eyes were facing cover as he hit it.
preText: First over of pace going for 15 doesn't dissuade Markram to go back to spin. There will be a difference in angle as Jansen comes on.

text: Length on leg, clipped to midwicket

text: Mulder finds short third! Magala's sharp, leaps to the left and plucks it. Athletic catch brings out celebrations and cheers from the crowd. Was on a length, wide. Mulder slashed hard. The edge off the cut was in Magala's reach and he took it low.
Length around off at 135kph, open-faced defence takes it to point
Whippy swivel pull takes it to short fine on the bounce. Was on a length and angling in.
Length on leg, swivels and tries to pull again. Appeal for caught behind is turned down, no review taken.

Pretorius is in the middle now.
