postText:
9:15pm Sunrisers now move up to second in the points table while Super Giants slide to the bottom. That's all from us tonight. On behalf of Vairvan, Ekanth, goodbye and take care! Do join us for our coverage tomorrow.

9:10pm Time for the presentation.

Quinton de Kock: "At the toss, I actually did not know what I wanted to do. If i think back now, I would have changed my mind. Batting is a concern. We have had two blowouts in two successive games. We have to start thinking about it and talking about it. We need points desperately. Hopefully we go [to Wanderers] and rock up."

Roelof van der Merwe, player of the match: "Was very enjoyable. The vibe was unbelievable and the band brings a different vibe. Just hitting my areas and lucky it's one of those nights when everything goes your way. I still enjoy playing the team game. I'd like to do it for a few more years and see how it lasts. Fortunate to play in front of this crowd at Gqeberha."

Aiden Markram: "We struggled to package a full game till today. Conditions yesterday were tough. It was a bit of learning and couple of meetings this morning we discussed about combating it. When a guy gives you a good start in powerplay, it's easier. Confident squad at the moment, but we have to restart come Tuesday. It is a big game, they are a great side. It will be another wicket and we will have to reassess it. The Bull Dog showed it. His passion rubs off and he does not look his age and hopefully carries on for ten more years."

8:59pm Gqeberha is painted Orange! And the brass band has had its time. And so have the others who have thronged St George's Park tonight. It has been a dominating performance from Sunrisers tonight that gives them the bonus point. Rossington set it up with his blitz at the top. Van der Merwe once again reminded South Africa of the good old times with his passion and six-for. All in all, a clinical outing for the home side.

Lots to reflect upon for Super Giants. How could they have done better with the ball? Both pace and spin travelled for them. And then their batting crumbled on the face of a tall ask. Moreover, why did de Kock slide down the order and not push Mayers down if indeed such a move was needed. Impacts their NRR as well. It will be a night of introspection for them.

text: Very full, almost-yorker length that hits Mendis on the pads. But that was angling down leg.
preText:
1.29pm The two umpires make their way to the middle. Out comes the highest run-getter of the tournament, Will Jacks, alongside a new partner, Kusal Mendis. As expected, Bjorn Fortuin to start with the new ball from around the wicket to Mendis, who takes first strike. No slips. Deep square leg and long off are out.

Keith: "Jason Roy is a power hitter, he doesn't adapt to slow surfaces having to pace an innings"

Not long before we get underway.

Tinura: "Rare to see Sri Lankans apart from Wanindu and Theekshana in overseas franchise leagues these days.. hoping Mendis can light up SA20." Dhananjaya did play an excellent hand last evening at ILT20. But, yes, really hoping Kusal Mendis does well. Think, the surface will suit his style of play.

1.20pm A bit of blow for Capitals, who are without Phil Salt. But Kusal Mendis, believe, is an excellent replacement. The surface is a used one, I can see Bjorn Fortuin turning his arm nice and early. Won't get too easy for the power-packed Captials line-up.

Mohd Irshad: "What really happened to Roy, looks like he is out of form since ages? Hope to see a good innings from him today." No better chance to play a big innings today and prove everyone wrong. Royals have backed him all-out.

1.10pm So, Jason Roy stays. He has been struggling big time so far this tournament, but obviously there is something Royals have seen that made them give him another go. Could Eoin Morgan have come in instead and Wihaan Lubbe gone up the order? Royals can't afford another slip-up.

Playing XIs:

Paarl Royals: Jason Roy, Jos Buttler (wk), Wihan Lubbe, Dane Vilas, Mitchell Van Buuren, David Miller (capt), Evan Jones, Ferisco Adams, Bjorn Fortuin, Lungi Ngidi, Tabraiz Shamsi

Pretoria Capitals: Kusal Mendis (wk), Will Jacks, Rilee Rossouw, Theunis de Bruyn, Shane Dadswell, James Neesham, Wayne Parnell (capt), Senuran Muthusamy, Eathan Bosch, Adil Rashid, Anrich Nortje

Toss: Wayne Parnell calls correctly and Pretoria Capitals will bat first. One change for Capitals with Phil Salt out sick and Kusal Mendis will make his debut. Paarl Royals are unchanged.

Wayne Parnell, Capitals captain: Used wicket, and it will at its best now. It will require a smarter brand of cricket. it is generally slower and lower here, but we just want the guys to go and express themselves.

David Miller, Royals captain: We were going to bat too. Lots of teams have beaten each other. We are not out but have to play some good cricket and get on the board. In a few areas, we slipped up, but just partnerships, we have to get that going. We've put our plans together, but it is about execution at the end of the day. No changes.

12.55pm Today's game will also see top two run-getters of the tournament - Will Jacks and Jos Buttler - in action. We will have the two highest wicket-takers of the tournament so far, Bjorn Fortuin and Anrich Nortje go head-to-head today. So, lots to look forward to. Toss in five minutes.

12.50pm Paarl are coming off two tough defeats, while Capitals are coming in much more confident with two straight wins. Capitals, in particular, have been relentless in the last couple of games. They blew away Durban's Super Giants for 80 last game and before that, had chased down 123 in just 13 overs against Joburg Super Giants.

12.40pm Hello and welcome to match No. 18 of the SA20 and today's clash is between table-toppers Pretoria Capitals and fifth-placed Paarl Royals, who will be playing in their home ground. I am Ashish Pant and will soon be joined by Danyal Rasool as we look ahead to what promises to be an exciting contest.

preText:
3.30pm Ready for the chase. The two openers, Wihaan Lubbe and Jason Roy, stride out to the middle. Oh, so no Buttler then. Has the heat got to him? Wayne Parnell with the new ball from over the wicket to Roy. Watch out for the one that decks back in. Gully in place.

3.29pm Won't be an easy chase for Royals on a surface that is certainly two-paced. Remember, MICT were able to defend 142 last evening. All eyes on Jason Roy as well. He has been struggling for runs. Can he get some form back? A quick start is crucial for the home side.

text: He's away! Back of a length but outside off. Just a bit of width and Roy thrashes the cut past point.
Fuller on middle and leg, he presents the full face of the bat and punches to mid-on

On a length on middle and leg, he works it to midwicket and sets off for a run
preText: Stays over to Lubbe. Wide slip in place

text: Woah, a wayward throw from Parnell almost costs his team some runs. Like Fortuin in the first innings. Full, coming into Roy who pushes back to the bowler. He charges back with a throw, that misses the stumps by a bit but the keeper does well to intercept to his left.
On a length outside off, he pats to mid-off

Length but on the pads and Lubbe just helps it past short fine leg for a four.

preText:
5.15pm Faf du Plessis said Neil Brand comes in at No. 3, but does not recall who is sitting out. For Eastern Cape, JJ Smuts and James Fuller are into the team. Time to welcome Danyal now, who will take you through the first half of Eastern Cape's innings.

5pm Time for the toss. Joburg Super Kings win the toss and opt to bowl.

Faf du Plessis says they have batted first in all the matches so far, and most teams have preferred chases so they would like to "join the bandwagon". Says the ball has been coming on to the ball better in the second innings and he hopes that stays the case.

Markram says he would have also chosen to bowl first. Credits the bowlers for their winning run. Says execution was not good in the first two matches, which they lost. Says that's something easy to live with as plans were in place.

4.45pm Hello and welcome to our coverage of today's SA20 clash between Sunrisers Eastern Cape and Joburg Super Kings. This will be the second game of the day, with MI Cape Town and Paarl Royals playing out a thriller right now. I'm Abhimanyu and I'll be joined soon by Danyal Rasool in the box. Eastern Cape, after losing their first two games, have won three on the trot and sit second on the points table. Joburg, meanwhile, started off with a win, then lost two in a row, got back to winning ways against table-toppers Pretoria Capitals and then lost again in the reverse fixture against Pretoria.

preText: Cricket nerd : "Hi there just wondering how it is that phangiso is still allowed to bowl even though he is under investigation?" The tournament guidelines state that a bowler can continue bowling while under investigation. You can read more about it here.
postText:
7.10pm So Sunrisers Eastern Cape only manage 127, getting bowled out with eight balls to go. Adam Rossington gave them momentum at the top of the order, but they kept losing wickets consistently. James Fuller and JJ Smuts, both of who came into the XI today, tried to get some runs at deep end, but they would feel they are short of a par total. With the ball, birthday boy Aaron Phangiso was sensational, picking up four wickets. Gerald Coetzee also grabbed four, while Romario Shepherd took one. Special mention also for the Joburg Super Kings skipper Faf du Plessis, who was just electric in the field. Alright, time for a short break. Be back with us soon for the chase!

Donovan Ferreira: "Bowling first for the first time now so to bowl a team out puts us in a good position. Ball is staying low, so if our batters get into good positions, we should be good. No better birthday present for Aaron Phangiso. Just hope our batters can do the job now."

Right, we're moments away from the start. Bjorn Fortuin will open the bowling. Ryan Rickleton on strike.

We've got the playing XIs for you here.

Rashid Khan says he wanted to bat first anyway. Maybe they could have sorted that out without all that toss faf. "We're well prepared, it's just about the mindset. We had a bad two games, but in T20 games you need to move on." MICT are unchanged.

Paarl Royals have won the toss and David Miller has no hesitation in bowling first.

"It's a little bit slower at this ground and the boundaries are bigger. We're going to try and see what they get." There's a few changes, and we'll bring you the XIs shortly.

Hello! Welcome to our coverage of the 16th match of the SA20, with Paar Royals taking on MI Cape Town.

postText: 3.10pm Cape Town finish with 142 for 9. It's a good recovery after they were reduced to 9 for 3 inside three overs. Grant Roelofsen and Rassie van der Dussen first stabilised the innings, and then George Linde found a couple of fours and six. For Paarl Royals, Bjorn Fortuin, Lungi Ngidi, Tabraiz Shamsi and Ferisco Adams all picked up two wickets each. Our Forecaster is giving Royals a 75% chance of winning. Can Cape Town surprise them? We will be back with the chase in a moment.

postText:
That's all from our side for this game. Let's head to Eastern Cape vs Super Kings.

Rashid Khan: We had a couple of losses. We lost the momentum in the last few overs. We tried to keep the things simple. We had a bad start but 140 was a good total here. And then a brilliant all-round effort by the bowlers. [On van der Dussen] He kept the innings till the end, it's good for us that he got runs under his belt. [On Linde] He has done an amazing job for us. You can send him up the batting order, can bowl him anywhere. Makes my job a lot easier. I felt whatever total we put up, the bowling unit we have, we can defend any total. Today we have shown that. It was a crucial win for us.

Jos Buttler: Very disappointed. We are in a position where we thought we were really in the game. Facing Jofra is always a big challenge. It's great for the England team to have him back. It's not the easiest to hit boundaries here but that's the challenge of playing at different surfaces. We had a discussion that we could chase 40-45 in the last four overs but then Davey got out. We both are disappointed with the result.

Jos Buttler is the Player of the Match, some consolation for him.

David Miller: I think 142 was a competitive total on this wicket. But I thought they were still below par but losing a couple of wickets in the powerplay didn't help. It was difficult to score boundaries at will. Buttler and I kept ourselves in but then I got out. A bit disappointed. But it's not all doom and gloom. We would like to string a few more partnerships. A quick turnaround tomorrow and hopefully we can pull it with the bat.

Time for the presentation ceremony.

5.00pm A superb defence from MI Cape Town; they pick up 4 points from the game to go No. 2 on the points table for the moment. Rashid Khan led from the front, going only for 16 - all singles - from his four overs. But before him, it was Linde who picked up two early wickets to rock Royals. Buttler and Miller anchored the chase. Miller fell for 26 but Buttler took them close. When Archer dropped him off Rabada, it seemed he might pull it off for Royals but Archer made amends by having him caught behind in the penultimate over to all but seal the win. Royals couldn't hit a single six in their innings.

wkt_text: KR Mayers c Rashid b Parnell 0 (2m 1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0.00
text: first ball wicket! What a decision to bowl Parnell with the new ball! Surprises Mayers with the short ball, aimed at Mayers' shoulder. He tries to nudge it leg side, but it takes a top edge and flies to Rashid at third man!
preText:
Chris Morris on comms says that there's a bit of grass on the deck but should be a batting surface. There's a breeze too which may aid some seam bowlers. And we have a new new-ball bowler with Parnell taking over from Bosch.

5.26pm Thanks, Danyal. Hello everyone. It is cloudy over here but hopefully the rain stays away.

We're ready to go in about five minutes. Sreshth will kick you off for the first ten overs.

Afeef : "The first century of the ILT20 has been scored today by Alex Hales. Now it's time for someone to become the first centurion of the SA20. Would be really cool if it can be Rossouw or QdK today."

"Very hot here in Durban," says Daz, presumably from Durban (though you never can be sure!) "I'm hoping for a super hot performance from the Giants"

We've got the Playing XI's for you here

Durban Super Giants have won the toss and elected to bat.

Welcome to our coverage of the 15th match of the SA20, where Durban's Super Giants take on table toppers Pretoria Capitals. We should have the toss for you very shortly

preText:
First look at the crowd, and they don't seem to mind the home team being all out for 80. They still look upbeat, enjoying the #scene created by CSA to promote the first season of their high-profile franchise league. Here's Kyle Mayers, he will get the ball to swing.

7.15pm According to ESPNcricinfo's forecaster, Capitals have a 1.58% chance of losing the game from here. Over in India, earlier this week, Vidarbha bowled out Gujarat for 54 in a chase of 73. The Super Giants can look for inspiration from there.

7.10pm A quick look at the points table says that Pretoria Capitals will extend their lead at the top of the table with a win today, let alone a bonus-point win. Durban's Super Giants will remain bunched up in the middle of the table with a defeat. Will Jacks and Phil Salt have batted at a run-rate of 10+ in the powerplay at the SA20.

7.05pm Thanks, Danyal. Hello all. That was NOT what the Durban home fans would've wanted to see on a Friday evening. An evening out could end up being an early finish for the home fans with Pretoria Capitals needing only 81 to win. Muthusamy was the pick of the bowlers, Parnell and Nortje stepped up too. A good outing for Adil Rashid as well.

James : "Without that over from Jimmy Neesham, things could have been even worse!"
postText: Just the start the home side needed.

If it is pad first - de Bruyn could be LBW. Oh yes, it is pad first - but the ball is swinging too much. Down the leg side again, ball-tracking says. de Bruyn survives, and the decision has been changed to four leg byes.

preText:
5.29pm Jason Roy and Jos Buttler stride out to the middle. The Sunrisers team is in a huddle. Gqamane to start off with the new ball. From over the wicket. One wide slip in place.

Corniel: "Excited to see young Jordan Hermann getting some game time today. He really looks to be a batsman with a lot of potential. Been getting big runs so far this season. "

Tim: "People in SA have been loving the SA20! So good to have fun, stress free cricket back in the country"

Rahim Chagani: "Finally Corbin 'Thor' Bosch get's a game for Paarl Royals! He was outstanding in the CPL for Barbados Royals - he always put his hand up to bowl in high-pressure situations and can hit boundaries for fun. Let's go Corbin"

Jarryd: "Why drop Smuts and continue with both Cox and Rossington? Neither have scored many runs in this tournament. " Yeah, was a bit surprised with that selection.

5.20pm So, changes on both sides. Personally, very excited to see Corbin Bosch and how he goes, here. Can Jason Roy find some form? It won't be easy against Sisanda Magala and Marco Jansen. Jansen will be keen on getting that ball to seam into Roy. Sunrisers have been in excellent chasing form. Can they make it three in three or will Royals continue their winning run? We'll find out in a bit.

Marius: "@Daz the excitement in South Africa comes from the fact that areas that don't often get major events have got a chance to see some of the best in the world. Places like paarl, gqeberha and Durban would be lucky to get one ODI in the summer. No crowds for 3 years! And that there hasn't even been a home South African game yet and we're getting into the later stages of summer!"

Anubhab Mukherj: "As a die-hard IPL and Delhi Capitals (nee Daredevils) fan since 2008, I am absolutely thrilled that we have this mini-IPL away from the IPL. Watching and loving every game here. Great win for us last night too."

Playing XIs

Paarl Royals: J Buttler (wk), J Roy, W Lubbe, D Miller (capt), E Morgan, E Jones, C Bosch, B Fortuin, C Yusuf, L Ngidi

Sunrisers Eastern Cape: A Rossington (wk), J Hermann, S Erwee, A Markram (capt), J Cox, T Stubbs, M Jansen, A Gqamane, R Van der Merwe, B Carse, S Magala,

Toss: Sunrisers win the toss and elect to field.

Aiden Markram, the Sunrisers captain: There have been a few people who have played here, and we think it is tough defending here. And, we have fielded everytime we won, so don't want to change that. Hopefully, we can put up a better batting performance. Two changes for us.

David Miller, the Royals captain: We would have bowled first as well. We have Corbin Bosch coming in. You need to have players come in and Evan Jones has done that. As the game goes goes, you formulate how things go. We are into our flow now, and looking forward to the game.

Not long before the toss.

Daz: "The tournament so far is being a success,the interest " Absolutely! The crowd has come in every single game. How's the buzz in South Africa about the tournament, in general?

4.55pm Both teams are coming off important wins. Royals got the better of Durban's Super Giants by ten runs, while Sunrisers beat MI Cape Town by two wickets with Marco Jansen playing the innings of his life. The lanky all-rounder smashed 66 off 27, which included smoking Rashid Khan for 28 in an over and three sixes against Kagiso Rabada. Sunrisers, who at one point, required 67 off the last five overs, got home with three balls to spare.

4.37pm Hello and welcome to the ball-by-ball commentary of match No. 14 of the SA20, which will see Paarl Royals take on Sunrisers Eastern Cape, in Paarl. I am Ashish Pant, and will soon be joined by Alan Gardner. This is the first fixture between the two sides in this tournament. Both teams have two wins each so far, but Royals, by the virtue of a bonus point win are on nine points and second on the table. Sunrisers, who were staring down the barrel after defeats in their first two games, has roared back in style but are still placed fifth out of six teams. They have a chance to move to second place with a win. Here's how the points table is stacked up.

postText:
Here's Brydon Carse: Happy with the team's performance. We stuck to the plans despite the two-paced wicket. As a bowling group, we did really well. We stuck to our original plan from the beginning. We wanted to bowl that back of a length balls. We had a slow start, but we have gelled as a team over the last two games. Hope we will chase this score down.

7.09pm That's as disciplined a bowling performance that you will see from a side. Sunrisers stuck to a plan right from the start and were relentless all the way through. It is a two-paced surface, no doubt, but the Royals batters did not get going at all. Jos Buttler fell early after a couple of false shots before Jason Roy departed to a wild slog. Wihan Lubbe was cleaned up by Carse for 28 while Morgan and Miller came and went. A lot of the batters got starts but no one really carried on. Carse, Markram and Van der Merwe all picked two wickets as Royals were restricted to 127. Will it be an easier chase for Sunrisers this time around? Join Alan in a bit to find out.

text: smashed on to the grass banks at cow corner, 97m six to finish! Sunrisers win by five wickets, and go second on the SA20 table - having been bottom yesterday morning!
postText: 8.55pm: It wasn't without a few nerves, as Sunrisers lost 3 for 1 inside a single over from Bjorn Fortuin, but in the end they get home for a pretty comprehensive win with 10 balls to spare. Jordan Hermann gave the chase a solid base and Paarl Royals were always going to struggle to defend a score of 127, despite Fortuin and Lungi Ngidi both picking up two in two - the former only denied a hat-trick by the DRS. Anyway, that's a wrap from Boland Park tonight, but there's still some live action in today's round-the-clock T20 schedule, SA Women looking to chase 148 against India over in East London. We'll be back for more, more, more tomorrow. Bye!

text: gone first ball, oh my word! Back of a length delivery outside off stump that leaves the batter very late. Hendricks has a nibble at it without any foot movement and feathers it through to the keeper. What a start this is for the Capitals!
preText:
5:28pm The players and umpires are making their way out to the middle. Like yesterday, du Plessis and Hendricks will open the batting for the Super Kings. Bosch with the new ball for the Capitals. Here we go!

Peter: "Well, well, well... Nandre Burger is in, this should be interesting "

Joburg Super Kings XI: Faf du Plessis (c), Reeza Hendricks, Leus du Plooy, Kyle Verreynne (wk), Lewis Gregory, Donovan Ferreira, Romario Shepherd, Alzarri Joseph, Gerald Coetzee, Nandre Burger, Aaron Phangiso

Pretoria Capitals XI: Phil Salt (wk), Will Jacks, Rilee Rossouw, Theunis de Bruyn, Shane Dadswell, James Neesham, Eathan Bosch, Wayne Parnell (c), Migael Pretorius, Adil Rashid, Anrich Nortje

5pm Time for the toss. Parnell gives the coin a spin, and it lands in the Capitals' favour. The Capitals will bowl first. Parnell says the trend is to bowl first at Centurion, hoping that batting gets better under lights. Unchanged XI for the Capitals. Two changes for the Joburg Super Kings - Nandre Burger and Lewis Gregory have been included. We will bring the playing XIs to you in a bit.

While we await the toss, do hop over to our coverage of the game between MI Cape Town and the Sunrisers Eastern Cape. MI Cape Town seem in control at this stage but you can never say never in this sport.

4:35pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of this SA20 fixture between the Joburg Super Kings and the Pretoria Capitals. Less than 24 hours ago, these teams played out an absolute humdinger, with the Super Kings holding their nerve just enough to emerge victorious.

Tonight, the Capitals have a chance to hit back on their home turf and prove that the result yesterday was just an anomaly. They would also want to ensure that they capitalize on clutch moments in the game, having been guilty of withering away the advantage yesterday. The Super Kings, on the other hand, would hope that their batting resurgence continues today and that they can give their bowlers something to defend, especially if they bat first against a potent Capitals bowling unit.

Plenty to look forward to, as always. And for the entirety of this contest, I (Shashwat) am going to be your eyes and ears. Buckle up folks, if this game is anything like yesterday, we are in for a crazy ride!

postText:
6:58pm A very peculiar innings comes to an end. The Super Kings began like a runaway train, with du Plessis dominating the powerplay. He blazed away to a 19-ball fifty and the visitors looked primed for a score in excess of 180. Once du Plessis fell, though, the Super Kings lost their way completely. They lost 7 wickets for 26 runs in the middle overs and that allowed the Capitals to tighten their grip on the game.

Speaking of the Capitals, well, they would be delighted with how this innings has turned out. They have a very chaseable target in front of them, and they might even be backing themselves to get a bonus point tonight. The hosts are certainly the happier of the two sides at the half-way stage and barring anything extraordinary, should get the job done. Do join us in a bit for the run-chase!

James Neesham: That was good fun. It was a strange innings. It felt we would be chasing 230-240 after the first six overs. Very happy to be chasing this score. I think it was a really good wicket with the new ball. It came on nicely.

postText:
8:22pm Right. That was in stark contrast to how the game between these two teams panned out yesterday. After four successive thrillers, though, such a contest was perhaps on the cards anyway. Tomorrow, the Paarl Royals will be back in action, and they will be taking on the Sunrisers Eastern Cape, fresh off a remarkable victory against MI Cape Town. Do join us for that match but until then, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of Binoy George and everyone at ESPNcricinfo. Goodbye, goodnight and take care!

8:20pm A very comfortable victory for the Capitals in the end. They did not have a mountain to scale in the second innings, and they flexed their batting muscles very early, with Jacks setting the tone. Rossouw also continued in a similar vein, with Salt ensuring that there were no further hiccups. The Super Kings looked out of sorts in both departments and after the high of yesterday's win, they have come crashing back down to earth and have plenty to ponder moving ahead.

text: gorgeous cover drive, and a sensational stop in the covers to prevent it going for four. What a start!
preText:
Jansen to open the bowling

Right, the sun is out on what looks a lovely day in Cape Town, and we should be good to go in a moment.

ShahSafeer: "Good to see Jofra back in the XI, even his rest days give his fans scares. Looking forward to seeing Archer, Olly and KG together at some point in the tournament!"

We've now got the starting line-ups for you.

The Sunrisers have won the toss and Aiden Markram has chosen to bowl

.

Aiden Markram says it's a fresh wicket, and that he hopes to exploit conditions upfront. They're comfortable chasing. Tom Abell in for Cox, Brydon in for James Fuller. He says they're looking to balance playing guys in form and rotating.

Rashid Khan also says wanted to bowl. Fresh wicket, looks good, according to him. Runs on the board will be good. Jofra and Rabada will play together, Olly misses out.

It might be early days in the SAT20, but there's still a gulf between these two sides in this top vs bottom clash.

12:50pm: Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of another double header in the SA20, it's the rematch from two days ago, MI Cape Town play host this time to Sunrisers Eastern Cape.

Danyal will be back for the chase. Stay tuned.

Roelof van der Merwe says they had a decent start, pulled it back a bit in the middle, good effort. Wicket played better back in the end, says chasing might be the right move. We were under pressure going in on the back of two losses last game, great performance the other day. Just need to chase this down now.

3:05pm: Potgieter and Odean take MI Cape Town to a decent score after the collapse after the second wicket. The stand was 48 off 23 could be the difference-maker. The spinners, though, were on top. Roelof van der Merwe and Ottniel Baartman took four wickets between them. Markram chipped in too. It looked to have undone the good work done by Ryan Rickelton and Grant Roelofsen, who added a 102. But the late runs give Rabada and Archer some cushion to go after the batters.

PietSkiet: "Very happy for Delano Potgieter, very underrated player that gets minimal chances, but almost always produce."

preText:
A bit of a false start as Hendricks pulls away at the last moment. And we go again!

5:28pm The players and umpires are making their way out to the middle. Hendricks and du Plessis to open the batting, as expected. Bosch with the new ball for the Capitals. Here we go!

Joburg Super Kings XI: Faf du Plessis (c), Reeza Hendricks, Leus du Plooy, Kyle Verreynne (wk), Donovan Ferreira, Romario Shepherd, Sibonelo Makhanya, Alzarri Joseph, Maheesh Theekshana, Gerald Coetzee, Aaron Phangiso

Pretoria Capitals XI: Phil Salt (wk), Will Jacks, Rilee Rossouw, Theunis de Bruyn, James Neesham, Shane Dadswell, Wayne Parnell (c), Migael Pretorius, Eathan Bosch, Adil Rashid, Anrich Nortje

5pm It's time for the toss. The Pretoria Capitals win the toss and elect to field first. The wicket looks a little drier than usual, says Parnell and he hopes that it gets better to bat on under lights. Unchanged XI for the Capitals. du Plessis reckons he would have bowled first too. Two changes for the Super Kings - du Plessis confirms that he will open the batting alongside Hendricks tonight. We will bring the playing XIs to you in a bit.

While we wait for this game to begin, do head over to the other game, where Durban's Super Giants need 51 runs off the final four overs. Klaasen and Maharaj are still at the crease and that match is far from done.

4:35pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of this SA20 clash between the Joburg Super Kings and the Pretoria Capitals. I am Shashwat Kumar and I will be your eyes and ears for everything that happens tonight in this potentially defining clash.

It is still early days in the tournament but with the Super Kings having already lost twice (in three games), the onus is on them to turn things around. Their batting has been a real concern so far. Even in the match that they won, they were saved by a heroic Donovan Ferreira display. Collectively, they have been found wanting and against a strong Pretoria Capitals bowling attack, their resolve, technique and character will be tested to the hilt.

As for the Capitals, well, they are the only team with a spotless record this season. They have won both of their fixtures and have looked a dominant outfit. Phil Salt and Will Jacks have been superb at the top of the order. Their middle and lower order has also stood up when required and their bowling, especially on true batting tracks, has done enough to keep the opposition in check. From that perspective, they will fancy their chances of getting the better of this misfiring Super Kings outfit. But with the Super Kings playing at home, things might not be as straightforward.

postText:
7:14pm Wow, that innings ebbed and flowed. The Super Kings got off to a decent start (better than what they have been doing this season, at least), with du Plessis setting the tone early on. Hendricks, though, struggled for momentum throughout his innings, and that rid the Super Kings of some crucial momentum in the powerplay and in the middle overs. Fortunately for them, du Plooy was playing a special knock at the other end, finishing with a 40-ball 75 that included several drool-worthy strokes. In fact, du Plooy has single-handedly powered the Super Kings to a total that they can very easily defend.

As for the Capitals, they would be ruing the number of runs they conceded in the final few overs. They ended up shipping 106 runs in the final 10 overs and that could still come back to haunt them. But on a strip that has progressively gotten better for batting, and with Jacks and Salt firing on all cylinders, the Capitals will back themselves to get the job done tonight. Do join us in a bit for the run-chase!

Leus du Plooy: It was a lot of fun, to be honest. Great to get to a good start with Faf and Reeza. To get an opportunity and to bat in front of our home crowd - what a feeling. The key was to just get used to the wicket. There was a little bit of a uppish bounce. Once you got used to it, you get good value here. (On the score) I think we did pretty well to get there. There was a stage where we could have gotten a bit more runs. I would have liked 175 but this is a competitive total. I back our bowlers.

1:26pm: The table mountain is in the background behind. Few people are in, under parasols, for the first of the double header. Pack your tanning lotions if you're planning to go to the ground today.

ChrisTaunton: "Any chance that you can explain why the guy you wrote up as a "superhero," namely Corbin 'Thor' Bosch has yet to appear in the Paarl Royal playing XI? From that write-up, I'd have imagined that he'd be involved in every single game!" As a selector, I think it's a difficult decision and... wait a minute.

Garv Asnani: "Where is Corbin Bosch? He hasn't played a game for Royals yet despite being in great form.." They have a couple of allrounders in Jones and Adams but that's a fair question. Bosch isn't in today. By the way, the playing XIs of both teams are here.

Reece Topley says they will be need to be on their toes. Says they have all bases covered and people are putting well-rounded performances. Having Lance Klusner and the local players is a huge advantage as they have imparted local knowledge.

Lungi Ngidi says he bowled to his field and that was the difference in the last game. He adds Tabraiz Shamsi rested in Durban and is good to go today. The heat can be a challenge but says with they should be alright given it's just 24 balls.

David Miller says Paarl Royals, of which he is captain, have a great balance. Still early in the comp, good to be back here. Says one or two results haven't gone their way. But if they do things well more often than not, it will.

Quinton de Kock, Durban's Super Giants' captain, says Keemo Paul has pulled up with an injury, Christian Jonker is in. Says it's been a great start, matter of continuing momentum, and that they have a couple of guys playing here and they feel chasing is better. He will bat at No 3 today.

1:02pm: Eight of the last ten games at Paarl have been won by the teams chasing. Quinton de Kock calls right and DSG choose to bowl

12:30pm: Ding ding ding, it's rematch time! It's Durban's Super Giants in the blue corner and Paarl Royals on the pink corner. These two teams met in Durban two days ago where Eoin Morgan's late punches couldn't get past the sustained Reece Topley's top-of-the-bail upper-cutting and Heinrich Klaasen's last-over knockout. Well, not every day is Sunday and not every boxing analogy is good. But tell you what, the quality of cricket here has been. So, get your kayfabe versions on, lift faces, turn heels 'cos the cricket's been great and Alan Gardner, AG the OG, will be here soon. Toss at 1pm local, stay tuned.

preText:
The Sunrisers Eastern Cape get into a huddle. It is a very important game for them. They are yet to get on board. Early wickets will be key. Marco Jansen to start proceedings. From over the wicket to Brevis. One slip in place. There is a good crowd in.

5.28pm Thanks, Ekanth and hello, all! How's everyone doing? The two umpire are out in the middle. The Cape Town openers, Dewald Brevis and Ryan Rickelton also stride out.

5:27pm: 26 degrees max, 84% humidity are the weather numbers according to the graphic. Should be fun watching the quicks in these conditions. Ashish will be here to kick things off. Say hi!

Darsh: "I usually skip leagues other than the IPL but something about the SAt20 seems enticing. How's the viewership been? Are the stadiums usually packed?" Don't know about the viewership but the crowd and atmosphere at the stadiums have been great.

"How is the weather mate?is it good?", asks (I think a different) Sam. There are clouds but looks pleasant as of now.

Sam goes meta with the T20-league universe: "Strange to see Rashid captaining the side against the Sunrisers"

Paresh: "Do we know why Jofra is not playing??" No official statement yet, he was rested last game so maybe that's continuing.

Rashid Khan says tough call with the toss as it is his first time here. Says they would have liked to bowl but batting first is fine with the bowling line-up they have. He says they have the best unit with great balance, and want to go according to the conditions. They want to give opportunities to the players. One change, Olly Stone is back for Waqar Salamkheil

Aiden Markram says they want to chase, says they want to get something upfront and chase it. Not the start we wanted, want to keep the outcome away for now and have the process now in place, and now we need to execute. Tom Abell is injured, Roelof is in. Rossington is in too.

5:02pm: Markram and Rashid are out for the toss. Markram tosses, Rashid calls heads. It's a tail. Sunrisers win the toss and will field

Afeef: "Looking forward to how Tristan Stubbs and Dewald Brevis play today. A big knock is due from Stubbs."

4:30pm: The weekend is over but worry not, cricket followers, the new week will load up with full-throttle action. The SA20, which started last week, has had great fanfare, conditions, and performances. Sunrisers Eastern Cape have had two losses chasing, they were off track early but had late flourishes which denied oppositions bonus points. They will look to turn things around and get their first-ever win. MI Cape Town have bookended a loss with two convincing wins, they have Kagiso Rabada and Jofra Archer, who was rested last game, in the mix. Dewald Brevis, the star at the top, could be on his way to the South African team. So there's rich talent coming through, which will be on display this evening. So revel in the action here with me, Ekanth, and Ashish, who will be on later. For those of you looking to keep up on past matches, here's our newsfile with brief reports to help you catch up.

text: A hint of movement into Brevis, who gets it off the inside half of his blade behind square for a run

preText: Stays over to the left-hander. FIne leg inside, third man in back. One slip in place

7.11pm A special knock from George Linde takes MI Cape Town to a respectable total on a surface that is aiding pace. The Sunrisers bowlers were all over Cape Town early on and applied the squeeze. Brevis could only manage 15 off 28 as Cape Town were reduced to 58 for 4 in the tenth over. But, RVD and Linde staged a 59-run stand off 33 balls. Linde was the aggressor as he finished on an unbeaten 63 off 28 balls with four fours and five sixes. It was down to him that Cape Town reached 158. Having said that, Sunrisers were disciplined all through with Baartman taking three wickets and Magala and Markram picking two. Can Sunrisers score their first points of the season? Won't be easy against a fiery Cape Town attack. Join Ekanth in a bit to find out.

postText:
The quality of cricket has been great, let's hope it continues. No teams without a win now. Thanks for tuning in. Hope you enjoyed our coverage. See you tomorrow for Paarl Royals vs Durban's Super Giants. You can catch up on the match reports and developments from the tournament on our SA20 newsfile. For now, it's me, Ekanth, signing off on behalf of my co-commentator, Ashish Pant, and our scorer, Venkat Raghav.

Aiden Markram, POTM and Sunrisers captain: Made it tough for ourselves but will make us happy which is important. I was gutten when out. Lot to learn and take away personally. Hats off to Jansen and Stubbs for clearing it. I get nervous watching from the side, knowing you can't make an impact. Certainly pleased now. Bowlers did a great job. Their margins of errors have been small, restricting MI under 160 was great. More of the same, I suppose. If we get the small things right, it will help us going forward.

Rashid Khan, MI Cape Town: It was close. I feel we were 15-20 short. But the way we bowled made me feel we were in till the end. It was a great performance, with the ball and in the field. It was a matter of going either side at the end. I feel we did a wonderful job. There are a few things to think about. It's important for us to move on, everyone knows their responsibility, enjoy, be mentally strong and give 100%.

The evening today started with cloud cover. The pitch was assisting the pacers, Cape Town understood they had to hit the pitch. Odean got it right, so did Rabada. They were outdone in parts by the batters but they were persistent.

The chase started with two early wickets. Curran got Rossington, a soft first-ball dismissal, and then got Smuts LBW. Erwee foiled with Aiden Markram who put up an aesthetic shot-making exhibition not devoid of power. I hope to have dreams of that cover drive he lofted into the outfield off Rabada. Rashid tried to shuffle his bowlers, tried to shake-up his act too. Got Erwee out to end a 92-run stand. Then Odean came on, got Markram for 50, trapped out Cox on review. The seesaw was in Cape Town's favour but Stubbs stood up tall. Got them on the verge of the win before Fuller finished it off.

9pm: Cracker of a game. Markram and Stubbs finding form are huge plusses for Sunrisers. MI Cape Town showed their mettle, fighting back from multiple difficult situations, taking it to the last over.

text: Short, wide, creamed through point. It was around fifth, Mayers stood still and opened the face, slapped it.
preText:
Slip in. Around

Manack, the offie, will open. Makes de Kock dropping himself down more interesting. Manack will get his match-up against a left hander up top as Mayers will take strike.

1:25pm: The sun is out in Durban, you can check the playing XIs of both teams here. The players are coming out. Mayers and Mulder will open for Super Giants. De Kock has demoted himself. Pommie Mbangwa suspects it might be to bring a left-right combination.

Anton: "Further to my previous message, I asked ChatGPT3 to write a reply on your behalf:"Even ChatGPT3 would know that no computer can replace the insight, experience and knowledge of a cricket commentator."Nailed it, imo." Okay, now I feel insecure and inferior about my future, past and present.

Stat Dan has a statty reminder: "Bonus point is not acheived by finishing chase within 16 overs, rather by achieving a run rate 1.25 times the opponent, which can be acheived in the 17th over, especially if game finishes with a 4 or 6, or if wides/no balls are bowled"

Keshav Maharaj says being a local makes others see him as a senior. Says it's a good wicket but could get slower due to the heat.

Quinton de Kock says it's a good toss to win and it's a good wicket. He says assessing the conditions and playing accordingly is key. Harmer is in. He says the crowds have been great and hopes it will continue to be. David Miller says it is strange to be here as part of the opposition and it's nice that the sun is out. Three seamers and three spinners are in. Shamsi is out due to injury.

1:02pm: Super Giants win the toss and bat first

Anton: "How do you feel about your future as a text ball-by-ball commentator in the age of ChatGPT3?" I don't have a creative answer, hopefully ChatGPT13 will in the future and I'm looking forward to it.

12.40pm Both teams lost their opening games, Royals to MI Cape Town and Super Giants to Joburg Super Kings, but bounced back strongly. Royals dismantled Super Kings by seven wickets and took home a bonus point as well. Super Giants on the other hand beat Cape Town by five wickets.

12.30pm Hello and welcome to the ball-by-ball commentary of Match No. 8 between Durban's Super Giants and Paarl Royals at Kingsmead, in Durban. I am Ashish Pant and will be joined by my co-commentator Ekanth shortly. Both Royals and Super Giants are coming off wins and will be looking to move up the points table.

shortText: Manack to de Kock, no run

text: Length outside off, punched to cover

postText: Harjas Singh: "Yesterday's match would have ended with a bonus point win even if they had scored the 107 in 16.1 overs (since the ratio would be 1.26). I wonder how many teams realize that. "

preText: Around

Overpitched on off at 130 kph, driven to cover

text: Full toss down leg. Wide. Beats the attempted fine flick

preText: Thanks, Ekanth. Setting up to be a tall score.

text: WALLOP! Tossed up outside off, but right in the arc for de Kock. He dances down the track, gets underneath and tonks it over deep midwicket for a mammoth six.

Two in two! Fortuin changes the angle, doesn't change his luck. Flatter on off, he stays in his crease this time around, gets the massive slog sweep out and pummels him over deep midwicket again, perhaps a bit squarer. The 50 of the partnership up as well.

shortText: Fortuin to de Kock, no run
text: quicker, flatter outside off, he cuts it hard but straight to point

shortText: Fortuin to de Kock, no run
text: slows it up and pushes it outside off. De Kock misses the cut.
Gets the reverse sweep out now, and slams Fortuin over short third. That was fired in at 100kph outside off, but de Kock was sure where that was heading.
Fires it quick on the leg stump. He looks for a hard slog, is rapped on the pads as the ball goes past the keeper. They collect a leg bye.
preText: Wihan Lubbe back into the attack from around the wicket

shortText: Lubbe to de Kock, no run
text: Fires it quick and full on off. He backs away but can only jam it back to the bowler

Oh, that is a super shot from de Kock. Tosses it up well outside off, he backs away, and has to reach for it. De Kock loses his bottom hand but still manages to clear the deep cover fence. That went 74 metres.
fired in on middle and leg, he tucks it to the on side for a run
fuller on middle stump, Mulder goes underneath and hacks it to deep midwicket powerfully

shortText: Lubbe to de Kock, no run

Time-out

text: Slower back of a length ball well outside off, was quite short as well. Mulder stands tall and cuts it hard to deep point.

Loses his line completely and sprays it way down leg. Buttler does well to his left.
preText: Around the wicket to de Kock

text: Fifty up for de Kock off just 27 balls, and he reaches there in style! On a length on the pads, he just gets across and whacks him over the deep fine leg fence.
back of a length pacy ball outside off, he cuts it to deep point
In the slot outside off, Mulder drills the cover drive but can't beat extra cover

But he loses his shape with the bat turning in his hands and can only find Miller, who comes forward and takes the catch. Mulder did his job, though.
attempted slower ball goes wrong as he sprays it well outside the tramline outside off. Called a wide
Low full toss very wide outside off. He reaches for it and helps it to deep point.
preText:
Ngidi from around the wicket

Heinrich Klaasen is the new man in. Perfect time for him to unleash the big one right away.

text: Back of a length ball on off, as Klaasen gets across and works it to deep midwicket.
preText: Over the wicket to Klaasen

text: Slower length ball outside off stump. He opens the face of the blade and drives it to the right of deep point for a couple of runs.
preText: Fine leg and third man are both in

wkt_text: Q de Kock c Jones b Ngidi 57 (44m 31b 5x4 4x6) SR: 183.87
text: Oh, that's a top catch from Jones running to his left from short third! Slower, length ball from Ngidi - was about 109kph. De Kock looks for a massive swipe, but is beaten by the pace and gets a massive top edge. Jones runs to his left, and also has to deal with the point fielder. He keeps his cool and puts in a dive to hold on.
Banged in short, he pulls it to deep midwicket.
preText: Paul in to face Ngidi from over the wicket.

text: Another slower back of a length ball from Ngidi. Klaasen absolutely drills his slap but straight to extra cover.
Loud shout from Fortuin and Buttler as Paul misses the reverse sweep! The umpire says not out, and they don't review. Looks like he got a bottom edge
slaps it past a diving cover, who half stops it and parries to long off
Slogs it away in some style! Fuller on off, he gets low down and sends it soaring over deep square leg.
short and wide, he goes back and thrashes him to deep cover off the backfoot.
goes down the track and collects it to on the full to clip it to deep midwicket
another quicker short of a length ball, was about 93 kph as he goes back and punches to long on
Another slower good length ball outside off, he cuts it hard to sweeper-cover.
preText: Adams back on from over the wicket

text: Does not quite get hold of the pull but that is the longer part of the boundary at deep midwicket. Banged in short, he miscues it for a run
Backs away, giving himself room and spots the slower ball early. Adams also pushed in wide, giving him the width. Klaasen frees his arms and slams him over wide long off
In the slot outside off, he looks to go again but misses. Probably tried a bit too hard there.
Slower ball into the surface as Klaasen goes down the track and pulls it to deep midwicket. He had to check his shot at the last moment, due to the slowness of the delivery
fuller length ball on the pads as Paul flicks it behind square for a couple of runs
Very wide, very full well outside off stump. He opens the face of the blade of squirts it over short third
pacy fuller ball outside off, he miscues his attempted swipe to long on
Length sliding down leg stump, but Klaasen had also gotten across a bit. Called a wide. I think that's a harsh call.
Length but keeps it well outside the arc of Paul, who tries to mow it over deep midwicket but misses
And, again, excellent bowling from Jones. Very full and outside off, he does time it at all and can only mistime it to long on

High, very high goes Klaasen, but just gets the height not distance. On a length outside off, he looks to pummel it away, but gets it off the bottom of his bat. Miller does his best running in from long on, dives forward, but the ball pops out at the last moment.
Shapes up for the switch hit does Klaasen, but does not connect and is rapped around the midriff area

wkt_text: KMA Paul c & b Ngidi 7 (17m 9b 0x4 0x6) SR: 77.77

Slower, dipping slower ball outside off. Excellent variations on display. Pretorius does not spot it and is beaten
preText: Pretorius is the new man in

text: Another slower back of a length ball on middle and leg. He is early into is pull, misses and is hit on the midriff. Ouch!
Ngidi has found his bearings really well here. On a length well outside off, Klaasen goes right across and can only help it to deep square leg.
This is just top bowling! Rolls his fingers over the ball again, outside off stump. Pretorius is into his shot way, way early. Misses it altogether.
He finally gets one in the middle and clears long on with ease! Slower back of a length ball that just sits up for the batter, who stays back and slams it straight down.
Perfect start to the final over! Length outside off, but he also gave Klaasen the width. He frees his arms and tonks him over deep cover.
Going, going, gone! Back of a length coming into the batter, who shapes up for the pull and absolutely smokes him over deep midwicket for a gigantic six.
Three in three! Klaasen is turning it on. Low full toss on off, Klaasen slaps him over deep midwicket.
Boo! Another low full toss outside off stump, he tonks it to deep cover all along the ground.
preText: Can he make it four and four

text: Doesn't quite get hold of the length ball with the bat turning in his hand and lofts it to deep cover
Mayers looks for swing, overdoes it. Ends up being a full toss outside off, driven to mid-off
preText:
Mayers will start for Durban.

3:28pm: Welcome back, umps shake hands as they walk out. Sunshine still strong. Quinton leads out his team, they have a huddle. Second-highest score on the ground in a T20, notes Chris Morris. English openers, Jason Roy and Jos Buttlers, will start for Royals. Big powerplay incoming?

text: Overpitched, driven, Paul does well at cover point to plug it. Shot played from outside off, flourish was there. Paul dove to the right and the ball went slow, diagonally to his right

Strangled down leg? No, and Super Giants won't review. Buttler went across, was standing on middle and off as he tried to clip it. Replay shows it deflected off the bat. Ticked the inside edge. Would have been out if reviewed.
Wide and full, guided to point
Full on leg, clipped to deep square

Topley's boots field the ball, they parry it towards midwicket. Full ball was driven back in the follow-through. Left boot it was
Length around off, driven with an open face towards cover

another back of a length ball into the body of Morgan who backs away again and cuts but straight to point

Strong drive and that is very well fielded at extra cover. Was shaping up to be a certain boundary the way Morgan slammed it. Fuller outside off, he drills the drive but can't beat extra cover. Brings up his fifty off 27 balls.
Full outside off, he thrashes the drive to extra cover. Morgan sets off for a run and would have been out by a mile it the fielder had hit. Makes it in the end.

What a way that would have been to depart. De Kock almost brought about a wicket out of nothing.

Time-out

preText:
Hello and welcome to ESPNCricinfo's live coverage of this encounter between MI Cape Town and Joburg Super Kings. MI Cape Town have won a game and lost the second match but it's still early days in the tournament and there are surely going to be many ups and downs as the inaugural edition of the SA20 progresses. MI Cape Town were clinical in the tournament opener against Paarl Royals where they registered a domineering win by eight wickets, chasing an untaxing 143 without any fuss as Brevis led the carnage with the bat and helped the side bag the bonus point as well whereas Archer made a resounding comeback to competitive cricket and took three wickets in his searing spell while Olly Stone was miserly as well. 

Come the second match against Durban's Super Giants, MI Cape Town lost the momentum during their batting in the middle overs and they couldn't press on the accelerator, ending up with 152 on the board. Archer and Rashid Khan were a tad expensive as well. On the other hand, Joburg Super Kings started off their tournament in style by overpowering Durban's Super Giants by 16 runs after a well-knit bowling display that helped them get over the line. Donovan Ferreira went all guns blazing with an unbeaten 82 off 40 deliveries while Romario Shepherd's blitzkrieg helped them post 190 on the board. However, they looked a completely different outfit in their second game against Paarl Royals as they folded out for 81 which didn't perturb Royals as they cruised to an easy victory, chasing the total with 57 balls to spare.

Kagiso Rabada and Odean Smith have been included in the side and Jofra Archer and Olly Stone are rested for this game

That's poetry in motion as Curran finishes the game in style, clears his front leg and mows it over extra cover for a scintillating boundary
postText:
Kagiso Rabada, Player of the Match: Good way to start, got early wickets, kept it as simple as possible and put them under pressure. The spinners kept getting wickets and made things easy for us. Lovely to play at Newlands, the crowd has been fantastic, and almost every game has been a sell-out. I wish I could make bowling look as easy as Joff (Archer), Olly Stone was slightly unlucky to have missed out today.

Rashid Khan, MI Cape Town captain: Amazing game, the way we bowled, KG, Linde and Waqar - it's a good win for us. We have played together in a Test match for Afghanistan, he (Waqar) has done well in the past and has the ability, he's ready to go and do well, happy for him. He had control in the middle overs. Linde, the way he bowled in the batting powerplay was superb, he and KG set the platform for us. It's not easy to bowl three overs in the powerplay for a spinner, but he always wanted to do it for us. I think we have the best bowling unit and so many options. We also have depth in the batting line-up, we saw it in the last game, it's just a matter of time before they step up and take the responsibility. The crowd has been great, they have come out to support us in large numbers over three games.

Faf du Plessis, Joburg Super Kings: T20 cricket is like a lottery, you can ride the momentum at times, two bad days, we will have to go back to Joburg and start over again. It could be a matter of confidence, you have three games in four days and it could be enough time to go back and work out. The pitch was slow and slightly worn out, their three spinners were certainly perfect for the conditions. We didn't have that luxury with our main spinner, Maheesh Theekshana, expected only later this week, would have been nice to win two on the road, but it's good to be going back home.

It was a walk-in-the-park affair for MI Cape Town as they register a comprehensive win over Joburg Super Kings. 107 was never really going to pose a serious challenge but this was a tricky and slow surface with the ball holding up and not coming nicely onto the bat. Brevis continued his rich vein of form and scored a quickfire 42 and Sam Curran's bright and breezy 15 made sure MI Cape Town get their second win of the SAT20. Earlier, George Linde and Rashid Khan didn't let Giants get off the hook and enjoyed bowling in spin-conducive conditions but it was Kagiso Rabada who hogged the limelight with his brilliant spell in which he only conceded 12 runs and picked up the vital scalp of Reeza Hendricks. The left-arm wrist-spinner Waqar Salamkheil spun a web around JSK as he took a leaf out of his captain Rashid Khan's book and made life arduous for the batters right from the get-go

That's it from tonight's coverage of the SA20. We look forward to your company tomorrow when Durban's Super Giants will lock horns with Paarl Royals. For now, it's goodbye from Rvel Zahid.

preText:
Afeef: "Parnell's cameo in the last match was a big reason for their win"

1.28pm: The players are making their way out to the middle. Salt and Jacks to open the batting for Capitals. Smuts with the ball

While Parnell said that batting first really doesn't concern them and that it was "very tough to rely on just 11 guys".

Markram said at the toss that they wanted to know what to chase. "We weren't up to the mark in the first game. We'd like to get better and hopefully do that this afternoon. You want to set the tone upfront and you look at your experienced players to do that," he said.

Sunrisers Eastern Cape XI: Sarel Erwee, JJ Smuts, Jordan Cox (wk), Aiden Markram (c), Tristan Stubbs, Marques Ackerman, Marco Jansen, James Fuller, Brydon Carse, Sisanda Magala, Ottniel Baartman.

Pretoria Capitals XI: Phil Salt (wk), Will Jacks, Rilee Rossouw, Theunis de Bruyn, Shane Dadswell, James Neesham, Migael Pretorius, Wayne Parnell (c), Eathan Bosch, Adil Rashid, Anrich Nortje.

1pm: Time for the toss. Sunrisers win toss and bowl first. One change for Capitals - Muthuswamy out, Pretorius in. For Sunrisers, Carse comes in for Crane.

12.35pm: Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of this SA20 clash between Pretoria Capitals and Sunrisers Eastern Cape in their reverse fixture. I am Srinidhi and will be joined by Ekanth as we bring you the live action.

In their previous meeting, Capitals beat Sunrisers by 23 runs after posting a total of 193. Phil Salt starred with an unbeaten 77 off 47 and helped Capitals to a competitive total which eventually proved enough.

For Sunrisers, JJ Smutt's 66 and Tom Abell's quickfire 40 went in vain and today, they would be hoping to bounce back and collect their first two points.

postText:
Over at Cape Town, the hosts have won the toss and have chosen to field against Super Kings. Check out the action there. Thanks for tuning on here. Goodbye from me, Ekanth, on behalf of Srinidhi, my co-commentator, and our scorers, Thilak and Raghav.

5:07pm: Handshakes and hugs as Capitals complete a comfortable win. It's their batters who set up the win. Parnell got back-to-back wickets in the second over. Smuts hung around but wasn't able to take off, unlike Markram, who made an attractive yet powerful 46. Once he fell, a cluster of wickets loomed but Jansen and Carse added a 60-run stand at over two-a-ball to deny the Capitals a bonus point. Adil Rashid's control and willingness to toss it up brought mixed results. Neesham and Bosch chipped in. Nortje got decent control and was pacy as usual.

text: full delivery darted into the batter on middle and off stump. Brevis falls over a touch and then plays all around it as the ball hits the pads
preText:
5:28pm The players are out in the middle. Rickelton and Brevis to open the batting for MI Cape Town. Mayers with the new ball for the Super Giants.

Durban's Super Giants XI: Quinton de Kock (c & wk), Kyle Mayers, Heinrich Klaasen, Wiaan Mulder, Jason Holder, Dwaine Pretorius, Keemo Paul, Hardus Viljoen, Prenelan Subrayen, Keshav Maharaj, Reece Topley

MI Cape Town XI: Dewald Brevis, Ryan Rickelton, Sam Curran, Rassie van der Dussen, Grant Roelofsen (wk), Delano Potgieter, George Linde, Rashid Khan (c), Duan Jansen, Olly Stone, Jofra Archer

5pm Time for the toss. Rashid gives the coin a spin, and it lands in the Super Giants' favour. The Super Giants will bowl first. de Kock says what happened here the other night influenced his decision to bowl first. Topley is a part of the XI today, de Kock confirms. Rashid says he would have bowled first too, although he is not too worried about what his team does first. We will bring the playing XIs to you shortly.

The pitch got visibly better for batting as the evening progressed on Tuesday. MI Cape Town won the toss that day and opted to field first. Will both captains look to do something similar if the coin falls in their favour tonight as well?

4:30pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of this SA20 clash between MI Cape Town and Durban's Super Giants. I am Shashwat Kumar and I will be your eyes and ears for everything that happens tonight.

MI Cape Town come into this game very high on confidence, having convincingly dispatched the challenge of the Paarl Royals in their opening fixture. Their star-studded bowling unit fired, as did Dewald Brevis with the bat. On paper, too, they have one of the strongest squads and would be hoping to build on that momentum tonight.

The Super Giants, meanwhile, had their moments against the Joburg Super Kings. They reduced them to 27-4, only to wither away the initiative and allow the Super Kings an avenue back into the game. With the bat, Quinton de Kock was at his belligerent best, stitching together a brilliant opening partnership. Apart from that, however, not a lot stood out, and that is what they would be hoping to rectify against MI Cape Town.

postText:
7:13pm A fairly topsy-turvy innings that ended with as many ebbs and flows as it started. MI Cape Town did not have the better of the early exchanges but they certainly dominated the last three overs. In between, the Super Giants' spinners threatened to apply the brakes and it required an excellent 60-run partnership between Linde and Roelofsen to keep them at bay.

With the ball gripping in the surface, and with MI Cape Town having a wonderful bowling attack, they are not out of it yet. If anything, this is a score that keeps both teams interested, and might make both of them feel they have a chance. Do join us in a bit for the run-chase!

preText: 7:26pm We are back. 153 to get against a very strong bowling unit. Do the Super Giants have enough firepower to get the job done? Let's find out. de Kock and Mayers to open the batting. Curran with the new ball for the hosts.

postText:
9:05pm Right. That will be a wrap from us for tonight. We have two more games lined up tomorrow, with the first of those being between the Pretoria Capitals and the Sunrisers Eastern Cape. Later in the evening, MI Cape Town will clash with Joburg Super Kings. Till next time, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of Ranjith. Goodbye, goodnight, and take care!

Quinton de Kock, Durban's Super Giants captain: (On the win) We needed that. I have played here quite a bit and I kind of understood the situation we were dealt with. (On batting second) I think the wickets will be a little slower in the day and they will come on a bit better in the night. (On the bonus point) We lost a couple of wickets and then concentrated on the win. Klaasen has been around a long time and in the end, we had to settle for just the win.

Kyle Mayers, Player of the Match: It was a good feeling to get the team across the finish line. (On the delivery to bowl Brevis) That is something I practice. My team always backs me to pick up a wicket in the first over and when a plan comes together, it feels good. I have a bit of skill and I try to show it every now and then. (Contest with Archer) Last time I batted against him in a match was probably in school. First time I batted against him since he has started playing for England. I really enjoyed the first game in Durban and it is really good for South African cricket (that fans are turning up)

Rashid Khan, MI Cape Town captain: We played good cricket in the last part of the first innings to put up that score. It was a matter of those 20-25 runs and that would have made the difference. The way the guys bowled and came back was a positive for us. Coming back tomorrow and we will hopefully not make the mistakes we did today. Whenever he (Stone) has been given an opportunity, he has stepped up. So good to have him and he has been amazing for us.

Time for the presentation!

8:51pm Well, Paul finished that in quite a hurry towards the end. But for a brief period, it looked like the Super Giants' boat was wobbling. Barring that spell, though, they were very good in the run-chase. Mayers set the tone at the top, with Klaasen and Mulder carrying on that momentum. Holder was his usual composed self in the middle, and was complemented beautifully by Paul, who grabbed the bull by the horns and tilted the game his team's way.

Plenty to ponder, meanwhile, for MI Cape Town. They would be looking at their batting display in particular and how they lost the initiative in the middle overs. Archer was also uncharacteristically expensive, as was Rashid and that, considering they were only defending 152, came back to haunt them.

text: Tossed up on leg, and Malan clips it away to the square leg fielder
preText:
1.29 pm The Joburg openers stride out to the middle. Paarl are out in the middle as well. Janneman Malan takes strike. Bjorn Fortuin will start off with the new ball! Here we go

Afeef: "The first round of matches have been really entertaining. Good signs for the SA20. And we have a double header on our hands today. Bring it on."

1.25pm We are just five minutes away from the start of the match. Will Joburg make it two in two or can Paarl get a win at home?

Paarl Royals XI: Jos Buttler(wk), Jason Roy, Wihan Lubbe, David Miller(capt), Dane Vilas, Eoin Morgan, Ferisco Adams, Evan Jones, Bjorn Fortuin, Lungi Ngidi, Tabraiz Shamsi

Joburg Super Kings XI: Janneman Malan, Reeza Hendricks, Faf du Plessis (capt), Kyle Verreynne (wk), Lewis Gregory, Donovan Ferreira, Romario Shepherd, George Garton, Alzarri Joseph, Lizaad Williams, Aaron Phangiso

1.09pm Faf du Plessis: "Lizaard wiliiams comes in today. We needed some more firepower at the back. The cluster of wickets that fell ,we want to address that. We batted beautifully, and Quinny batted well, but we challenged well with the ball and want to continue that."

David Miller: "We would have batted first as well. It might get a little slower as the tournament goes on. We have started well with the ball. Evan Jones comes in today and Lungi Ngidi, so the two big men back."

1.05pm One change for Joburg, with Lizaad Williams coming in. Lungi Ngidi and Evan Jones are in for Paarl.

1.02pm Joburg Super Kings have won the toss and opted to bat.

12.55pm We are just five minutes away from the toss. Today is also the first double-header in the SA20. MI Cape Town take on Durban's Super Giants in the evening match.

12.37pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of the fourth match of the inaugural SA20. I am Abhimanyu and will soon be joined by Ashish Pant in the box. It's Joburg Super Kings taking on Paarl Royals today. While Joburg got off to a winning start, thanks to Donovan Ferreira's stunning knock, Paarl lost out to MI Cape Town in their first game.

postText:
3.02pm That will be it for me from this match. Ashish will join you shortly to take you through the second innings.

3.01pm Fortuin: "Obviously we weren't up to the mark in our last game. Having Lungi back really helps. As a unit we needed to improve our performance and that's what we did. [On his bowling] High risk high reward, that's the way I look at it. There are chances you get smashed around but it brings about more wickets. [On it being a quick chase] Never say never, but yeah we are confident we can win this but let's keep our feet on the ground."

3.00pm What a fantastic bowling performance from Paarl! Fortuin got three wickets bowling in the powerplay, while Lungi Ngidi picked up one. The slide continued well past the powerplay and only a 26-run partnership for the last wicket that helped stretch the innings for as long as it did go. Paarl will now be chasing 82.

postText:
4.32pm Excellent comeback from Royals, who take the bonus point and rise up on the points table. Super Kings have a few top order issues to solve, and that might involve Faf du Plessis going back to the opening spot. That's it from this game, but we are done yet. Not long before MI Cape Town take on Durban's Super Giants and Shashwat Kumar has fired up the comms. I am signing off, though. Have a good evening, everyone. Ciao!

David Miller: Coming back from the loss, but the guys were up for it, and they got to a great start. They were clinical in the backend. To get the bonus point was great. Thought of giving an extra over to Lungi. We were ahead of the game, and wanted to put the pressure on. We had the bowlers to sort the death bowling. There are always decisions that are 50-50. It is about trusting our instincts. It is about committing your instincts, and the bowlers helped us. [On the chase] We never discussed anything. Eighty is a niggly total. The guys know their roles, and we got to a good start.

Bjorn Fortuin is the Player of the Match: Pretty special; our last game wasn't ideal, we had to bounce back and we did that. [Opening the bowling] It is quite high-risk, high-reward. It does present opportunities to pick wickets. The conditions played into our hands and we made good use of it today.

First up, Faf du Plessis: Disappointed with the start, that's stating the obvious. There was nice pace, and the bowlers got the ball to come through nicely early. The conditions got better in the second innings, but the score was way lower. Assessing the wickets is the most important thing, but it is about giving us a bit more time. We have not done it two games in a row. There were a few soft dismissals, but I think, we need to buck up. [On going at the top of the order] Just felt maybe Janneman needs an opening spot more than I do. It's something we have scratched our heads long enough, and we might go back.

Time for presentation.

4.12pm Paarl Royals had conceded a bonus point in their opening game, they make sure they get on board with one. Top performance from them. A win that was thoroughly set up by the bowlers, who blew Super Kings for 81. The batters then, led by Jos Buttler, came out all guns firing to make light work of the chase. Jason Roy fell early, but Wihan Lubbe and Buttler kept them going. David Miller then came out, smashed a six to get to 9000 T20 runs before Buttler sealed the win by seven wickets.

text: full delivery floated outside off stump. Salt crouches down low and lifts it over extra cover. The ball, though, plugs in the outfield and stops well inside the ropes
preText:
5:27pm The players are making their way out to the middle. Salt and Jacks will open the batting for the Capitals. Jansen with the new ball for the hosts. Here we go!

Both captains, at least at the toss, thought that there was an advantage bowling first. The Capitals, though, do not have time to brood over it. They have batting firepower in abundance and might want to put the hosts under pressure very early.

Pretoria Capitals XI: Phil Salt (wk), Will Jacks, Rilee Rossouw, Theunis de Bruyn, Shane Dadswell, James Neesham, Senuran Muthuswamy, Wayne Parnell (c), Eathan Bosch, Adil Rashid, Anrich Nortje

Sunrisers Eastern Cape XI: Sarel Erwee, JJ Smuts, Tom Abell, Jordan Cox (wk), Aiden Markram (c), Tristan Stubbs, Marco Jansen, James Fuller, Mason Crane, Sisanda Magala, Ottniel Baartman

5pm Time for the toss. Sunrisers Eastern Cape win the toss and bowl first.. Cox, Abell, Fuller and Crane are the four overseas players for the Sunrisers Eastern Cape. Parnell says he would have bowled first as well and reckons it is a typical St. George's wicket. We will bring the playing XIs to you very shortly.

Not long left before the toss now. One game has been won by the team batting first, with MI Cape Town chasing down a total comfortably in the opener. What will the captains want to do if they win the toss today?

Sandeep Jalda : "Hi Shashwat.. who do you reckon has balanced side .. I'm rooting for Stubbs to go big today" -- Both teams can hold their own, although I would say that the Capitals look slightly better balanced. A bowling unit comprising of Little, Nortje, Parnell and Adil Rashid will be tough to get away on most days. de Bruyn, Jacks, Rossouw, Salt and Mendis (whenever he is available) make up a pretty good batting line-up too.

The SA20 has gotten off to a brilliant start, with fans flocking the stadium and enjoying plenty of excellent cricket. Yesterday, Donovan Ferreira lit up the competition with a splendid knock, only for Quinton de Kock to almost better it. In the end, though, the Joburg Super Kings did just enough to hold their nerve. A couple of days ago, MI Cape Town flexed their muscles against the Paarl Royals. So, today, both teams have an opportunity to lay down a marker of their own and tell the rest of the competition that they mean business.

Markram will lead the Sunrisers, and Parnell will captain the Capitals. A bit of history there, with Markram leading South Africa to the U-19 World Cup title in the past and Parnell falling at the final hurdle against Virat Kohli's boys all those years ago. Nevertheless, this is a new chapter for both teams and individuals, and with the quality on display, both would be disappointed if they can't get their campaign off to the perfect start.

4:35pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of Match 3 of the inaugural edition of the SA20 between the Pretoria Capitals and the Sunrisers Eastern Cape. I am Shashwat Kumar and I will be your eyes and ears for tonight, hoping to narrate everything that happens in this potentially fascinating encounter.

postText:
8:12pm It was a stop-start beginning, with all the rain, lightning and thunder around. Salt, though, was a constant before the interruption and after it, scoring a sumptuous 47-ball 77. He set the tone at the start, ensured the momentum did not drop through the middle and propelled the Capitals to 193. He was helped along the way, with Neesham and Parnell producing crucial cameos.

The hosts, meanwhile, would be ruing their inability to keep things quiet during the middle overs. They picked up three wickets in the powerplay but could not quite make that count. Their plans towards the end were also not up to scratch, meaning that they now have a mountain to climb. Do join us in a bit for the run-chase!

Phil Salt: I had to hold myself back with the wickets falling. We felt we were probably behind the game but then Jimmy and Parny came out and batted like that. It is a very good score. (On English players in SA20) It is good to have Jacks and Little. Lucky to be spending a month with them. The crowd is unbelievable. It took me by surprise a little when they were singing and chanting our names.
