postText:
10pm Right. That will be that from us for this game. But the action does not stop in the SA20. In fact, we have two games tomorrow. Do join us for both matches tomorrow, with MI Cape Town, Joburg Super Kings, Paarl Royals and Durban's Super Giants all in action. Until then, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of Ranjith. Goodbye, goodnight and take care!

9:55pm A fairly comfortable victory for the Capitals in the end. They produced a superb batting effort, which was then backed up by an equally impressive bowling display. Nortje, in particular, breathed fire throughout his spell and caused the Sunrisers all sorts of problems with his sheer pace. The hosts could have batted better but take nothing away from what was a clinical bowling performance.

Speaking of the Sunrisers, well, they would be largely unhappy with how this game panned out. Apart from Smuts' fifty, and a brief rear-guard action by Abell, Fuller and Stubbs, there was not much to shout home about. This could, in all likelihood, be their strongest eleven too, meaning that they will have to figure out a way to make better use of their resources moving forward.

text: full delivery darted into the batter on middle and leg stump. Malan comes forward and flicks it down the ground to get off the mark
preText:
5:28pm Bright sunshine to greet the players at Kingsmead. Malan and Hendricks to open the batting. Mayers with the new ball for the Super Giants.

5:25pm Not long left before the start of play now. This game has already taken a fascinating turn. The Super Kings expect the wicket to get slower; the hosts expect it to get better. Three spinners in the Super Giants' line-up too, and it will be interesting to see how they use them.

Joburg Super Kings XI: Faf du Plessis, Janneman Malan, Reeza Hendricks, Kyle Verreynne (wk), Lewis Gregory, Donovan Ferreira, Romario Shepherd, George Garton, Alzarri Joseph, Malusi Siboto, Aaron Phangiso

Durban's Super Giants XI: Quinton de Kock (c & wk), Kyle Mayers, Matthew Breetzke, Heinrich Klaasen, Prenelan Subrayen, Jason Holder, Wiaan Mulder, Dwaine Pretorius, Keshav Maharaj, Akila Dananjaya, Keemo Paul

5:01pm Time for the toss. de Kock gives the coin a twirl, and it falls the Super Kings' way. Joburg Super Kings will bat first. du Plessis says the track could get slower and that that influenced his decision. de Kock says that he would have bowled first anyway. We will bring the playing XIs to you in a bit.

The track at Cape Town yesterday was quite tacky at the start and gradually improved as the game progressed. The match today is at Durban but will the captains be tempted to win the toss and bowl first again, considering batting could get easier under the lights?

4:30pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of Match 2 of the SA20 between the Durban's Super Giants and the Joburg Super Kings. I am Shashwat Kumar and akin to yesterday, will bring to you all the updates from what promises to be an exciting encounter.

Part of why I say that is because of the presence of excellent players on both sides. The Super Kings will be led by Faf du Plessis, who continues aging like fine wine. Alzarri Joseph, Janneman Malan, Kyle Verreynne, Lewis Gregory and Romario Shepherd are also part of the side. Durban, meanwhile, will be captained by Quinton de Kock, with the likes of Heinrich Klaasen, Jason Holder and Johnson Charles adding muscle and firepower to their batting unit. In Dwaine Pretorius, they also have a wonderful death-bowling option up their sleeve.

Apart from that, both teams would also be eager to match the early gauntlet MI Cape Town laid down yesterday. An opening game defeat usually does not define how a campaign will transpire, although it is an occasion that neither teams wants to pass up either.

postText:
9:15pm Right. That will be that from us for tonight. Hope you enjoyed our coverage, and we hope to have your company tomorrow as well, with the Pretoria Capitals taking on the Sunrisers Eastern Cape. Till then, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of M Venkat Raghav. Goodbye, goodnight and take care!

9:10pm Wow, that was some game. It ebbed and flowed throughout but just when it mattered, the Super Kings held their nerve. They produced a superb death-bowling display, which ultimately proved to be the difference between the two sides, considering the Super Giants shipped 91 runs in their last six overs. The visitors' spinners also rose to the occasion, conceding only 79 runs in the 12 overs that they bowled, including a couple of crucial wickets.

There was plenty of batting class on display too. de Kock nearly turbocharged an improbable run-chase. Unfortunately for the hosts, none of the batters apart from Mayers provided de Kock the sort of support he needed. That was in stark contrast to how the Super Kings batters joined hands with Ferreira earlier in the evening, ensuring that they posted a total that was ultimately beyond the Super Giants' reach.

preText:
5:28pm The players are walking out to the middle. Buttler and Lubbe will open the batting for the Royals; Linde to take the new ball for MI Cape Town. Here we go!

Afeef: "So who's gonna light up the opening night of SA20 like Brendon McCullum did in the IPL over 15 years ago? Could it be Jos Buttler? -- Considering the kind of form he is in, you would not want to bet against it

Paarl Royals XI: Jos Buttler (wk), Jason Roy, Wihan Lubbe, David Miller (c), Eoin Morgan, Dane Vilas, Ferisco Adams, Bjorn Fortuin, Ramon Simmonds, Codi Yusuf, Tabraiz Shamsi

MI Cape Town XI: Rassie van der Dussen, Grant Roelofsen (wk), Dewald Brevis, Ryan Rickelton, Delano Potgieter, George Linde, Sam Curran, Rashid Khan (c), Duan Jansen, Olly Stone, Jofra Archer

As for the ground dimensions, there is a shorter boundary to one side and batters might look to exploit it. AB de Villiers reckons that 160 will be par on this surface and that 180 will be a fantastic score.

Rashid Khan gives the coin a spin, and it lands in MI Cape Town's favour! MI Cape Town will bowl first! Jofra Archer is in the side, confirms Rashid. Rabada, though, has been rested after his excursions in Australia. Rashid says no decision has been made yet on Livingstone and that he hopes he will get well soon. Miller says he would have bowled first too. Miller also admits that they have not changed their eleven, despite having to bat first. We will bring the playing XIs to you for both sides in a bit!

Not long left for the toss now. What will the captain winning the toss want to do? We are about to find out!

The SA20 will see a few novel rules being introduced, including teams being able to name their playing XIs after the toss. Here is all you need to know about the competition, and much more.

4:30pm Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of this opening SA20 fixture between MI Cape Town and the Paarl Royals. Plenty of expectations around the inception of this competition, and this game is perhaps the best advertisement it could get, with several world-class stars potentially on display.

MI Cape Town will be led by Rashid Khan, arguably the best white-ball spinner in the world. Dewald Brevis, Jofra Archer, Kagiso Rabada, Rassie van der Dussen and Sam Curran are also part of the set-up. The Royals, meanwhile, have appointed David Miller as their skipper. Dane Vilas, Jason Roy, Jos Buttler and former England captain Eoin Morgan make up a strong batting unit, with Lungi Ngidi and Tabraiz Shamsi providing penetration with the ball.

So, a cracking curtain-raiser awaits us, and for the entirety of this contest, I (Shashwat) am going to be your eyes and ears. Sit back, relax and enjoy!

postText:
8:58pm Right. That will be a wrap from us for tonight. The action, though, comes thick and fast at the SA20. Tomorrow, the Durban Super Giants will take on Joburg Super Kings in what promises to be another cracking contest. Until next time, this is me (Shashwat) signing off on behalf of Chandan. Goodbye, goodnight, and take care!

Rashid Khan, MI Cape Town captain: So happy to be starting the new competition with a win. The way we started was great, and then we finished off with our batting. Looking forward to keeping this momentum. The bowling unit we have is one of the best. As a captain it makes it so easy because you have bowlers who can bowl in different stages. We just need to focus on doing the right things. (On Archer) It is super hard to be out for so long and come back this way. It was delightful to watch. We saw him in practice and knew that he was ready to go. It was superb to watch and to be on the same side as him. (On Brevis) The way he played tonight was amazing. We know how good a hitter he is. Important thing was he took his time today and the way he managed his innings and finished it was important. The youngsters are stepping up, they are working hard and I am super excited to be with them for the next few weeks. (On the crowd) Thanks to the crowd for supporting their home team. It is great to see the crowd back and it feels amazing to have that kind of support.

David Miller, Paarl Royals captain: Not a good start from us. I think it was a little bit tough when we batted up front. It got a little easier as it went on. They batted really well and put us under pressure. Our execution was not great either. We slipped up in a few areas and we will have to learn from those areas. There were two dropped catches which is never good in a T20 competition. He (Brevis) struck it really sweet and at the back end, it was good to watch. When Morgs and I were batting, we were having that chat about how him (Archer) being fit is great for world cricket.

Dewald Brevis, Player of the Match: I want to thank the crowd for their great support. I really enjoyed batting every single ball. I want to thank god as well. Absolutely grateful for this opportunity to play in front of my home crowd. He (de Villiers) has played a key role in my development as a player. He helped me through a lot and gives me the right advice. I could not wait for this day to see him (Archer), run in and bowl at pace. It is not my worry (that Livingstone and Rabada are returning), it is the other teams' worry.

8:40pm Well, that was a fairly comfortable victory for MI Cape Town in the end. They set the tone with the ball, with Archer and Stone leading the way. Then, it was time for Brevis and Rickelton to take the game away from the Royals. The latter got the ball rolling in the powerplay, before Brevis took over. Even after Rickelton was dismissed, Brevis continued on his merry way, notching up a 41-ball 70, which included four fours and five sixes. Brevis' belligerence also meant that MI Cape Town hunted down the total inside 16 overs, securing a bonus point win at the first time of asking.

Plenty to ponder, meanwhile, for the Royals. Their bowling plans lacked clarity and their accuracy also left a lot to be desired. They were not great with the bat either, and might have to revaluate how best to use the power hitters in their side. There is still a long way to go, and from that perspective, they might be happy that their bad day at the office is now out of the way.
